# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: world-war-i
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:world-war-i/1-000-000-000] In standard form, it is written as **1 × 109**.
[src:world-war-i/1-000-000-000] The metric prefix giga indicates 1,000,000,000 times the base unit.
[src:world-war-i/1-000-000-000] One billion years may be called an *eon* in astronomy or geology.
[src:world-war-i/1-000-000-000] Previously in British English (but not in American English), the word "billion" referred exclusively to a million millions (1,000,000,000,000).
[src:world-war-i/1-000-000-000] However, this is not common anymore, and the word has been used to mean one thousand million (1,000,000,000) for several decades.
[src:world-war-i/1-000-000-000] The term ***milliard*** could also be used to refer to 1,000,000,000; whereas "milliard" is rarely used in English, variations on this name often appear in other languages.
[src:world-war-i/1-000-000-000] In the Indian numbering system, it is known as 100 crore or 1 arab.
[src:world-war-i/1-000-000-000] It is a common metric used in macroeconomics when describing national economies.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] The **sixth cholera pandemic** (1899–1923) was a major outbreak of cholera beginning in India, where it killed more than 800,000 people, and spreading to West Asia, North Africa, Eastern Europe, and Russia.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] The outbreak of the pandemic is thought to have started at the Haridwar Kumbh Mela.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] The epidemic spread to Europe via Punjab, Afghanistan, Persia, and southern Russia.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] An outbreak of cholera in New York City from 1910 to 1911 is thought to be part of the pandemic, having spread through infected people aboard the steamship *Moltke* which was transporting passengers from Naples.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] In 1913, there was a cholera outbreak in forces of the Romanian Army which were taking part in military operations of the Second Balkan War in Bulgarian areas.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] According to Leonard Rogers, following an outbreak of cholera at the Haridwar Kumbh Mela, the epidemic spread to Europe via Punjab, Afghanistan, Persia, and southern Russia.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] The last cholera outbreak in the United States was in 1910–1911 when the steamship *Moltke* brought infected people to New York City from Naples.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] Vigilant health authorities isolated the infected on Swinburne Island, built in the nineteenth century as a quarantine facility.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] Eleven people died, including a health care worker at the island hospital.
[src:world-war-i/1899-1923-cholera-pandemic] In 1913, the Romanian Army, while invading Bulgaria during the Second Balkan War, suffered a cholera outbreak that provoked 1,600 deaths.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The **Russian Revolution of 1905**, also known as the **First Russian Revolution**, was a revolution in the Russian Empire which began on 22 January 1905 and led to the establishment of a constitutional monarchy under the Russian Constitution of 1906, the country's first formal constitution.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In the years leading up to the revolution, impoverished peasants had become increasingly angered by repression from their landlords and the continuation of semi-feudal relations.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Further discontent grew due to mounting Russian losses in the Russo-Japanese War, poor conditions for workers, and urban unemployment.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 9 January] 1905, known as "Bloody Sunday," a peaceful procession of workers, led by Georgy Gapon, was fired on by guards outside the tsar's Winter Palace in Saint Petersburg.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Widespread demonstrations and traditional strikes spread all over the empire and were brutally repressed by the tsar's troops.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In June, sailors on the battleship *Potemkin* undertook a mutiny, and in October, a strike by railway workers turned into a general strike in Saint Petersburg and Moscow.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The striking urban workers established councils, including the inaugural St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg Soviet of Workers' Deputies, in order to debate their course of action.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The influence of revolutionary parties, in particular the Socialist Revolutionary Party and Russian Social Democratic Labour Party, quickly escalated.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] At the same time, the reactionary pro-monarchist Black Hundreds began attacks on intellectuals, revolutionaries, and the Jewish population.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In response, the tsar issued the "October Manifesto," a pledge to create a legislative assembly, halt censorship and violations of freedom of association, and expand the right to vote.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The constitution, drafted by Sergei Witte and enacted on 6 May [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 23 April] 1906, did not bring an end to the turmoil, as anti-monarchist revolutionaries continued to rally for a constituent assembly.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The movement for reform fragmented into conservative Octobrist and liberal Kadet factions, and the left split into moderates content with the reforms and those who desired a full overthrow of the tsar.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The revolution slowly fizzled out in the face of harsh repression as troops returned after the end of the Russo-Japanese War in September 1905.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Despite popular participation, the Duma was unable to issue laws of its own and often came into conflict with the tsar, who in July 1906 dissolved the first Duma and appointed Pyotr Stolypin as prime minister, who set about restoring autocratic rule.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In June 1907, the second Duma was dissolved and an electoral reform which favored the propertied classes was decreed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Many historians contend that the Revolution of 1905 set the stage for the Russian Revolution of 1917, which saw the monarchy abolished, the tsar executed, and a socialist state established.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Calls for the peasantry and workers to take power by force were present in the 1905 revolution, but many of the revolutionaries who were in a potential position to lead were either in exile or in prison while it took place.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Because the Russian economy was tied to European finances, the contraction of Western money markets in 1899–1900 plunged Russian industry into a deep and prolonged crisis; it outlasted the dip in European industrial production.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This setback aggravated social unrest during the five years preceding the Revolution of 1905.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Tsarist government recognised some of these problems, albeit shortsightedly.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Minister of the Interior Vyacheslav von Plehve had said in 1903 that, after the agrarian problem, the most serious issues plaguing the country were those of the Jews, the schools, and the workers, in that order.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Any residual popular loyalty to Tsar Nicholas II was lost on 22 January 1905, when his soldiers fired upon a crowd of protesting workers, led by Georgy Gapon, who were marching to present a petition at the Winter Palace.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Every year, thousands of nobles in debt mortgaged their estates to the noble land bank or sold them to municipalities, merchants, or peasants.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] By the time of the revolution, the nobility had sold off one-third of its land and mortgaged another third.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The peasants had been freed by the emancipation reform of 1861, but their lives were generally quite limited.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The government hoped to develop the peasants as a politically conservative, land-holding class by enacting laws to enable them to buy land from nobility by paying small installments over many decades.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Such land, known as "allotment land", would not be owned by individual peasants but by the community of peasants; individual peasants would have rights to strips of land to be assigned to them under the open field system.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] A peasant could not sell or mortgage this land, so in practice he could not renounce his rights to his land, and he would be required to pay his share of redemption dues to the village commune.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This plan was intended to prevent peasants from becoming part of the proletariat.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The situation worsened as masses of hungry peasants roamed the countryside looking for work and sometimes walked hundreds of kilometers to find it.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Desperate peasants proved capable of violence.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] These violent outbreaks caught the attention of the government, so it created many committees to investigate the causes.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The committees concluded that no part of the countryside was prosperous; some parts, especially the fertile areas known as the "black-soil region", were in decline.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Although cultivated acreage had increased in the last half century, the increase had not been proportionate to the growth of the peasant population, which had doubled.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Nineteenth-century Russians saw cultures and religions in a clear hierarchy.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Non-Russian cultures were tolerated in the empire but were not necessarily respected.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Culturally, Europe was favored over Asia, as was Orthodox Christianity over other religions.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] For generations, Russian Jews had been considered a special problem.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Jews constituted only about 4% of the population but were concentrated in the western borderlands.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The government's treatment of Jews, although considered a separate issue, was similar to its policies in dealing with all national and religious minorities.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] There was growing impatience with their inferior status and resentment against "Russification".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Russification is cultural assimilation definable as "a process culminating in the disappearance of a given group as a recognizably distinct element within a larger society".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Besides the imposition of a uniform Russian culture throughout the empire, the government's pursuit of Russification, especially during the second half of the nineteenth century, had political motives.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] After the emancipation of the serfs in 1861, the Russian state was compelled to take into account public opinion, but the government failed to gain the public's support.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Another motive for Russification policies was the Polish uprising of 1863.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Unlike other minority nationalities, the Poles, in the eyes of the Tsar, were a direct threat to the empire's stability.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] After the rebellion was crushed, the government implemented policies to reduce Polish cultural influences.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In the 1870s the government began to distrust German elements on the western border.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Russian government felt that the unification of Germany would upset the power balance among the great powers of Europe and that Germany would use its strength against Russia.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The government thought that the borders would be defended better if the borderland were more "Russian" in character.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The culmination of cultural diversity created a cumbersome nationality problem that plagued the Russian government in the years leading up to the revolution.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The economic situation in Russia before the revolution presented a grim picture.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The government had experimented with *laissez-faire* capitalist policies, but this strategy largely failed to gain traction within the Russian economy until the 1890s.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, "agricultural productivity stagnated, while international prices for grain dropped, and Russia's foreign debt and need for imports grew.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] War and military preparations continued to consume government revenues.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In the 1890s, under Finance Minister Sergei Witte, a crash governmental program was proposed to promote industrialization.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] His plan was successful and during the 1890s "Russian industrial growth averaged 8 percent per year.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Railroad mileage grew from a very substantial base by 40 percent between 1892 and 1902." Ironically, Witte's success in implementing this program helped spur the 1905 revolution and eventually the 1917 revolution because it exacerbated social tensions.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The "peasant worker" saw his labour in the factory as the means to consolidate his family's economic position in the village and played a role in determining the social consciousness of the urban proletariat.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The new concentrations and flows of peasants spread urban ideas to the countryside, breaking down isolation of peasants on communes.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Industrial workers began to feel dissatisfaction with the Tsarist government despite the protective labour laws the government decreed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Some of those laws included the prohibition of children under 12 from working, with the exception of night work in glass factories.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Employment of children aged 12 to 15 was prohibited on Sundays and holidays.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Workers had to be paid in cash at least once a month, and limits were placed on the size and bases of fines for tardy workers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Employers were prohibited from charging workers for the cost of lighting of the shops and plants.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Despite these labour protections, the workers believed that the laws were not enough to free them from unfair and inhumane practices.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] At the start of the 20th century, Russian industrial workers worked on average 11-hours per day (10 hours on Saturday), factory conditions were perceived as grueling and often unsafe, and attempts at independent unions were often not accepted.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Many workers were forced to work beyond the maximum of 11+1⁄2 hours per day.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Others were still subject to arbitrary and excessive fines for tardiness, mistakes in their work, or absence.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Russian industrial workers were also the lowest-wage workers in Europe.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Although the cost of living in Russia was low, "the average worker's 16 rubles per month could not buy the equal of what the French worker's 110 francs would buy for him." Furthermore, the same labour laws prohibited the organisation of trade unions and strikes.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Dissatisfaction turned into despair for many impoverished workers, which made them more sympathetic to radical ideas.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] These discontented, radicalized workers became key to the revolution by participating in illegal strikes and revolutionary protests.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The government responded by arresting labour agitators and enacting more "paternalistic" legislation.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Some of these groups organised in Moscow, Odessa, Kiev, Nikolaev, and Kharkov, but these groups and the idea of police socialism failed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] From 1900 to 1903, the period of industrial depression caused many firm bankruptcies and a reduction in the employment rate.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Employees were restive: they would join legal organisations but turn the organisations toward an end that the organisations' sponsors did not intend.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Workers used legitimate means to organise strikes or to draw support for striking workers outside these groups.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] A strike that began in 1902 by workers in the railroad shops in Vladikavkaz and Rostov-on-Don created such a response that by the next summer, 225,000 in various industries in southern Russia and Transcaucasia were on strike.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] These were not the first illegal strikes in the country's history but their aims, and the political awareness and support among workers and non-workers, made them more troubling to the government than earlier strikes.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The government responded by closing all legal organisations by the end of 1903.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Minister of the Interior, Plehve, designated schools as a pressing problem for the government, but he did not realize it was only a symptom of antigovernment feelings among the educated class.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Students of universities, other schools of higher learning, and occasionally of secondary schools and theological seminaries were part of this group.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Student radicalism began around the time Tsar Alexander II came to power.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Alexander abolished serfdom and enacted fundamental reforms in the legal and administrative structure of the Russian empire, which were revolutionary for their time.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] He lifted many restrictions on universities and abolished obligatory uniforms and military discipline.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This ushered in a new freedom in the content and reading lists of academic courses.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In turn, that created student subcultures, as youth were willing to live in poverty in order to receive an education.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] As universities expanded, there was a rapid growth of newspapers, journals, and an organisation of public lectures and professional societies.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The 1860s was a time when the emergence of a new public sphere was created in social life and professional groups.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This created the idea of their right to have an independent opinion.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The government was alarmed by these communities, and in 1861 tightened restrictions on admission and prohibited student organisations; these restrictions resulted in the first ever student demonstration, held in St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg, which led to a two-year closure of the university.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The consequent conflict with the state was an important factor in the chronic student protests over subsequent decades.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The atmosphere of the early 1860s gave rise to political engagement by students outside universities that became a tenet of student radicalism by the 1870s.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Student radicals described "the special duty and mission of the student as such to spread the new word of liberty.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Students were called upon to extend their freedoms into society, to repay the privilege of learning by serving the people, and to become in Nikolai Ogarev's phrase 'apostles of knowledge'." During the next two decades, universities produced a significant share of Russia's revolutionaries.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Prosecution records from the 1860s and 1870s show that more than half of all political offences were committed by students despite being a minute proportion of the population.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] "The tactics of the left-wing students proved to be remarkably effective, far beyond what any of the students would have dreamed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] They took up problems that were unrelated to their "proper employment", and displayed defiance and radicalism by boycotting examinations, rioting, arranging marches in sympathy with strikers and political prisoners, circulating petitions, and writing anti-government propaganda.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This disturbed the government, but it believed the cause was lack of training in patriotism and religion.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Therefore, the curriculum was "toughened up" to emphasize classical language and mathematics in secondary schools, but defiance continued.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Expulsion, exile, and forced military service also did not stop students.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The events of 1905 came after progressive and academic agitation for more political democracy and limits to Imperial rule in Russia, and an increase in strikes by workers against employers for radical economic demands and union recognition, (especially in southern Russia).
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] As an example, Trotsky who would assume a central role in the 1905 revolution, would write several proclamations urging for improved economic conditions, political rights and the use of strike action against the Imperial regime on behalf of workers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Many socialists view this as a period when the rising revolutionary movement was met with rising reactionary movements.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] As Rosa Luxemburg stated in 1906 in *The Mass Strike*, when collective strike activity was met with what is perceived as repression from an autocratic state, economic and political demands grew into and reinforced each other.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Russian progressives formed the Union of Zemstvo Constitutionalists in 1903 and the Union of Liberation in 1904, which called for a constitutional monarchy.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Russian socialists formed two major groups: the Socialist Revolutionary Party (founded in 1902), which followed the Russian populist tradition, and the Marxist Russian Social Democratic Labour Party (founded in 1898).
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In late 1904 liberals started a series of banquets (modeled on the *campagne des banquets* leading up to the French Revolution of 1848), nominally celebrating the 40th anniversary of the liberal court statutes, but actually an attempt to circumvent laws against political gatherings.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The banquets resulted in calls for political reforms and a constitution.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In November 1904 a Zemsky Congress (Russian: Земский съезд)—a gathering of zemstvo delegates representing all levels of Russian society—called for a constitution, civil liberties and a parliament.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 30 November] 1904, the Moscow City Duma passed a resolution demanding the establishment of an elected national legislature, full freedom of the press, and freedom of religion.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Similar resolutions and appeals from other city dumas and zemstvo councils followed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Emperor Nicholas II made a move to meet many of these demands, appointing liberal Pyotr Dmitrievich Sviatopolk-Mirsky as Minister of the Interior after the July 1904 assassination of Vyacheslav von Plehve.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 12 December] 1904, the Emperor issued a manifesto promising the broadening of the zemstvo system and more authority for local municipal councils, insurance for industrial workers, the emancipation of Inorodtsy and the abolition of censorship.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The crucial demand—that for a representative national legislature—was missing in the manifesto.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Worker strikes in the Caucasus broke out in March 1902.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Strikes on the railways, originating from pay disputes, took on other issues and drew in other industries, culminating in a general strike at Rostov-on-Don in November 1902.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Daily meetings of 15,000 to 20,000 heard openly revolutionary appeals for the first time, before a massacre defeated the strikes.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] But reaction to the massacres brought political demands to purely economic ones.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In 1904, massive strike waves broke out in Odessa in the spring, in Kiev in July, and in Baku in December.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This all set the stage for the strikes in St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg in December 1904 to January 1905 seen as the first step in the 1905 revolution.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Another contributing factor behind the revolution was the Bloody Sunday massacre of protesters that took place in January 1905 in St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg sparked a spate of civil unrest in the Russian Empire.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Lenin urged Bolsheviks to take a greater role in the events, encouraging violent insurrection.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In doing so, he adopted SR slogans regarding "armed insurrection", "mass terror", and "the expropriation of gentry land", resulting in Menshevik accusations that he had deviated from orthodox Marxism.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In turn, he insisted that the Bolsheviks split completely with the Mensheviks; many Bolsheviks refused, and both groups attended the Third RSDLP Congress, held in London in April 1905 at the Brotherhood Church.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Lenin presented many of his ideas in the pamphlet *Two Tactics of Social Democracy in the Democratic Revolution*, published in August 1905.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In December 1904, a strike occurred at the Putilov plant (a railway and artillery supplier) in St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Sympathy strikes in other parts of the city raised the number of strikers to 150,000 workers in 382 factories.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 8 January] 1905, the city had no electricity and newspaper distribution was halted.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Controversial Orthodox priest Georgy Gapon, who headed a police-sponsored workers' association, led a huge workers' procession to the Winter Palace to deliver a petition to the Tsar on Sunday, 22 January [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The troops guarding the Palace were ordered to tell the demonstrators not to pass a certain point, according to Sergei Witte, and at some point, troops opened fire on the demonstrators, causing between 200 (according to Witte) and 1,000 deaths.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The event became known as Bloody Sunday, and is considered by many scholars as the start of the active phase of the revolution.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg provoked public indignation and a series of massive strikes that spread quickly throughout the industrial centers of the Russian Empire.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Polish socialists—both the PPS and the SDKPiL—called for a general strike.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] By the end of January 1905, over 400,000 workers in Russian Poland were on strike (see Revolution in the Kingdom of Poland (1905–1907)).
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Half of European Russia's industrial workers went on strike in 1905, and 93.2% in Poland.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] There were also strikes in Finland and the Baltic coast.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In Riga, 130 protesters were killed on 26 January [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 13 January] 1905, and in Warsaw a few days later over 100 strikers were shot on the streets.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] By February, there were strikes in the Caucasus, and by April, in the Urals and beyond.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In March, all higher academic institutions were forcibly closed for the remainder of the year, adding radical students to the striking workers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] A strike by railway workers on 21 October [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 8 October] 1905 quickly developed into a general strike in Saint Petersburg and Moscow.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This prompted the setting up of the short-lived Saint Petersburg Soviet of Workers' Delegates, an admixture of Bolsheviks and Mensheviks headed by Khrustalev-Nossar and despite the Iskra split would see the likes of Julius Martov and Georgi Plekhanov spar with Lenin.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Leon Trotsky, who felt a strong connection to the Bolsheviki, had not given up a compromise but spearheaded strike action in over 200 factories.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 13 October] 1905, over 2 million workers were on strike and there were almost no active railways in all of Russia.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Growing inter-ethnic confrontation throughout the Caucasus resulted in Armenian–Tatar massacres, heavily damaging the cities and the Baku oilfields.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] With the unsuccessful and bloody Russo-Japanese War (1904–1905) there was unrest in army reserve units.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] On 2 January 1905, Port Arthur was lost; in February 1905, the Russian army was defeated at Mukden, losing almost 80,000 men.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] On 27–28 May 1905, the Russian Baltic Fleet was defeated at Tsushima.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Witte was dispatched to make peace, negotiating the Treaty of Portsmouth (signed 5 September [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In 1905, there were naval mutinies at Sevastopol (see Sevastopol Uprising), Vladivostok, and Kronstadt, peaking in June with the mutiny aboard the battleship *Potemkin*.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The mutineers eventually surrendered the battleship to Romanian authorities on 8 July in exchange for asylum, then the Romanians returned her to Imperial Russian authorities on the following day.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Some sources claim over 2,000 sailors died in the suppression.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The mutinies were disorganised and quickly crushed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Despite these mutinies, the armed forces largely remained loyal, if dissatisfied—and were widely used by the government to control the 1905 unrest.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Nationalist groups had been angered by the Russification undertaken since Alexander II.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Poles, Finns, and the Baltic provinces all sought autonomy, and also freedom to use their national languages and promote their own culture.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Muslim groups were also active, founding the Union of the Muslims of Russia in August 1905.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Certain groups took the opportunity to settle differences with each other rather than the government.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Some nationalists undertook anti-Jewish pogroms, possibly with government aid, and in total over 3,000 Jews were killed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] On 12 January 1905, the Tsar appointed Dmitri Feodorovich Trepov as governor in St Petersburg and dismissed the Minister of the Interior, Pyotr Sviatopolk-Mirsky, on 18 February [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] He appointed a government commission "to enquire without delay into the causes of discontent among the workers in the city of St Petersburg and its suburbs" in view of the strike movement.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The commission was headed by Senator Nikolay Shidlovsky, a member of the State Council, and included officials, chiefs of government factories, and private factory owners.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] It was also meant to have included workers' delegates elected according to a two-stage system.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Elections of the workers delegates were, however, blocked by the socialists who wanted to divert the workers from the elections to the armed struggle.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 20 February] 1905, the commission was dissolved without having started work.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Following the assassination of his uncle, the Grand Duke Sergei Aleksandrovich, on 17 February [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 4 February] 1905, the Tsar made new concessions.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 18 February] 1905 he published the *Bulygin Rescript*, which promised the formation of a consultative assembly, religious tolerance, freedom of speech (in the form of language rights for the Polish minority) and a reduction in the peasants' redemption payments.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 11 and 12 May] 1905, about 300 Zemstvo and municipal representatives held three meetings in Moscow, which passed a resolution, asking for popular representation at the national level.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 24 May] 1905, Nicholas II had received a Zemstvo deputation.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Responding to speeches by Prince Sergei Nikolaevich Trubetskoy and Mr Fyodrov, the Tsar confirmed his promise to convene an assembly of people's representatives.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Tsar Nicholas II agreed on 2 March [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 18 February] to the creation of a State Duma of the Russian Empire but with consultative powers only.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] When its slight powers and limits on the electorate were revealed, unrest redoubled.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Saint Petersburg Soviet was formed and called for a general strike in October, refusal to pay taxes, and the en masse withdrawal of bank deposits.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In June and July 1905, there were many peasant uprisings in which peasants seized land and tools.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Disturbances in the Russian-controlled Congress Poland culminated in June 1905 in the Łódź insurrection.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Surprisingly, only one landlord was recorded as killed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Far more violence was inflicted on peasants outside the commune: 50 deaths were recorded.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Anti-tsarist protests displaced onto Jewish communities in the October 1905 Kishinev pogrom.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The October Manifesto, written by Sergei Witte and Alexis Obolenskii, was presented to the Tsar on 14 October [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] It closely followed the demands of the Zemstvo Congress in September, granting basic civil rights, allowing the formation of political parties, extending the franchise towards universal suffrage, and establishing the Duma as the central legislative body.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Tsar waited and argued for three days, but finally signed the manifesto on 30 October [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 17 October] 1905, citing his desire to avoid a massacre and his realisation that there was insufficient military force available to pursue alternative options.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] He regretted signing the document, saying that he felt "sick with shame at this betrayal of the dynasty ... the betrayal was complete".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] When the manifesto was proclaimed, there were spontaneous demonstrations of support in all the major cities.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The strikes in Saint Petersburg and elsewhere officially ended or quickly collapsed.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The concessions came hand-in-hand with renewed, and brutal, action against the unrest.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] There was also a backlash from the conservative elements of society, with right-wing attacks on strikers, left-wingers, and Jews.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] While the Russian liberals were satisfied by the October Manifesto and prepared for upcoming Duma elections, radical socialists and revolutionaries denounced the elections and called for an armed uprising to destroy the Empire.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Some of the November uprising of 1905 in Sevastopol, headed by retired naval Lieutenant Pyotr Schmidt, was directed against the government, while some was undirected.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] It included terrorism, worker strikes, peasant unrest and military mutinies, and was only suppressed after a fierce battle.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Trans-Baikal railroad fell into the hands of striker committees and demobilised soldiers returning from Manchuria after the Russo–Japanese War.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Tsar had to send a special detachment of loyal troops along the Trans-Siberian Railway to restore order.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 22 and 24 November], there was a general strike by Russian workers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The government sent troops on 7 December, and a bitter street-by-street fight began.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] A week later, the Semyonovsky Regiment was deployed, and used artillery to break up demonstrations and to shell workers' districts.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] 5 December], with around a thousand people dead and parts of the city in ruins, the workers surrendered.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] After a final spasm in Moscow, the uprisings ended in December 1905.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] According to figures presented in the Duma by Professor Maksim Kovalevsky, by April 1906, more than 14,000 people had been executed and 75,000 imprisoned.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Historian Brian Taylor states the number of deaths in the 1905 revolution was in the "thousands" and notes one source that puts the figure at over 13,000 deaths.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Following the Revolution of 1905, the Tsar made last attempts to save his regime, and offered reforms similar to most rulers when pressured by a revolutionary movement.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The military remained loyal throughout the Revolution of 1905, as shown by their shooting of revolutionaries when ordered by the Tsar, making overthrow difficult.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] These reforms were outlined in a precursor to the Constitution of 1906 known as the October Manifesto which created the Imperial Duma.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Russian Constitution of 1906, also known as the Fundamental Laws, set up a multiparty system and a limited constitutional monarchy.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries were quelled and satisfied with the reforms, but it was not enough to prevent the 1917 revolution that would later topple the Tsar's regime.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] There had been earlier attempts in establishing a Russian Duma before the October Manifesto, but these attempts faced dogged resistance.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] One attempt in July 1905, called the Bulygin Duma, tried to reduce the assembly into a consultative body.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] It also proposed limiting voting rights to those with a higher property qualification, excluding industrial workers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Both sides—the opposition and the conservatives—were not pleased with the results.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Another attempt in August 1905 was almost successful, but that too died when Nicholas insisted on the Duma's functions be relegated to an advisory position.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The October Manifesto, aside from granting the population the freedom of speech and assembly, proclaimed that no law would be passed without examination and approval by the Imperial Duma.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Manifesto also extended the suffrage to universal proportions, allowing for greater participation in the Duma, though the electoral law on 11 December still excluded women.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Nevertheless, the tsar retained the power of veto.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Propositions for restrictions to the Duma's legislative powers remained persistent.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] A decree on 20 February 1906 transformed the State Council, the advisory body, into a second chamber with legislative powers "equal to those of the Duma".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Not only did this transformation violate the Manifesto, but the Council became a buffer zone between the tsar and Duma, slowing whatever progress the latter could achieve.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Even three days before the Duma's first session, on 24 April 1906, the Fundamental Laws further limited the assembly's movement by giving the tsar the sole power to appoint/dismiss ministers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Adding insult was the indication that the Tsar alone had control over many facets of political reins—all without the Duma's expressed permission.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The trap seemed perfectly set for the unsuspecting Duma: by the time the assembly convened on 27 April, it quickly found itself unable to do much without violating the Fundamental Laws.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Defeated and frustrated, the majority of the assembly voted no confidence and handed in their resignations after a few weeks on 13 May.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The attacks on the Duma were not confined to its legislative powers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] By the time the Duma opened, it was missing crucial support from its populace, thanks in no small part to the government's return to Pre-Manifesto levels of suppression.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Soviets were forced to lay low for a long time, while the zemstvos turned against the Duma when the issue of land appropriation came up.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The issue of land appropriation was the most contentious of the Duma's appeals.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Duma proposed that the government distribute its treasury, "monastic and imperial lands", and seize private estates as well.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Duma, in fact, was preparing to alienate some of its more affluent supporters, a decision that left the assembly without the necessary political power to be efficient.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Nicholas II remained wary of having to share power with reform-minded bureaucrats.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] When the pendulum in 1906 elections swung to the left, Nicholas immediately ordered the Duma's dissolution just after 73 days.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Hoping to further squeeze the life out of the assembly, he appointed a tougher prime minister in Petr Stolypin as the liberal Witte's replacement.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Much to Nicholas's chagrin, Stolypin attempted to bring about acts of reform (land reform), while retaining measures favorable to the regime (stepping up the number of executions of revolutionaries).
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] After the revolution subsided, he was able to bring economic growth back to Russia's industries, a period which lasted until 1914.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] But Stolypin's efforts did nothing to prevent the collapse of the monarchy, nor seemed to satisfy the conservatives.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Stolypin died from a bullet wound, fired by a revolutionary, Dmitry Bogrov, on 5 September 1911.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Even after Bloody Sunday and defeat in the Russo-Japanese War, Nicholas II had been slow to offer a meaningful solution to the social and political crisis.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] At this point, he became more concerned with his personal affairs such as the illness of his son, whose struggle with haemophilia was overseen by Rasputin.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Nicholas also refused to believe that the population was demanding changes in the autocratic regime, seeing "public opinion" as mainly the "intelligentsia" and believing himself to be the patronly 'father figure' to the Russian people.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Sergei Witte, the minister of Russia, frustratedly argued with the Tsar that an immediate implementation of reforms was needed to retain order in the country.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] It was only after the Revolution started picking up steam that Nicholas was forced to make concessions by writing the October Manifesto.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Issued on 17 October 1905, the Manifesto stated that the government would grant the population reforms such as the right to vote and to convene in assemblies.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Ensuring that no law would be passed without the consent of the Imperial Duma.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Despite what seemed to be a moment for celebration for Russia's population and the reformists, the Manifesto was rife with problems.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Aside from the absence of the word "constitution", one issue with the manifesto was its timing.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] By October 1905, Nicholas was already dealing with a revolution.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Another problem surfaced in the conscience of Nicholas himself: Witte said in 1911 that the manifesto was written only to get the pressure off the monarch's back, that it was not a "voluntary act".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In fact, the writers hoped that the Manifesto would sow discord into "the camp of the autocracy's enemies" and bring order back to Russia.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] One immediate effect it did have, for a while, was the start of the Days of Freedom, a six-week period from 17 October to early December.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This period witnessed an unprecedented level of freedom on all publications—revolutionary papers, brochures, etc.—even though the tsar officially retained the power to censor provocative material.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This opportunity allowed the press to address the tsar, and government officials, in a harsh, critical tone previously unheard of.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The freedom of speech also opened the floodgates for meetings and organised political parties.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In Moscow alone, over 400 meetings took place in the first four weeks.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Some of the political parties that came out of these meetings were the Constitutional Democrats (Kadets), Social Democrats, Socialist Revolutionaries, Octobrists, and the far-rightist Union of the Russian People.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Among all the groups that benefited most from the Days of Freedoms were the labour unions.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In fact, the Days of Freedom witnessed unionisation in the history of the Russian Empire at its apex.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] At least 67 unions were established in Moscow, as well as 58 in St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg; the majority of both combined were formed in November 1905 alone.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] For the Soviets, it was a watershed period of time: nearly 50 of the unions in St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg came under Soviet control, while in Moscow, the Soviets had around 80,000 members.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] This large sector of power allowed the Soviets enough clout to form their own militias.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg alone, the Soviets claimed around 6,000 armed members with the purpose of protecting the meetings.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Perhaps empowered in their newfound window of opportunity, the St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg Soviets, along with other socialist parties, called for armed struggles against the Tsarist government, a war call that no doubt alarmed the government.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Not only were the workers motivated, but the Days of Freedom also had an earthquake-like effect on the peasant collective as well.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Seeing an opening in the autocracy's waning authority thanks to the Manifesto, the peasants, with a political organisation, took to the streets in revolt.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In response, the government exerted its forces in campaigns to subdue and repress both the peasants and the workers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Consequences were now in full force: with a pretext in their hands, the government spent the month of December 1905 regaining the level of authority once lost to Bloody Sunday.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Ironically, the writers of the October Manifesto were caught off guard by the surge in revolts.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] One of the main reasons for writing the October Manifesto bordered on the government's "fear of the revolutionary movement".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] In fact, many officials believed this fear was practically the sole reason for the Manifesto's creation in the first place.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Among those more scared was Dmitri Feodorovich Trepov, governor general of St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Petersburg and deputy minister of the interior.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Trepov urged Nicholas II to stick to the principles in the Manifesto, for "every retreat ... would be hazardous to the dynasty".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Russian Constitution of 1906 was published on the eve of the convocation of the First Duma.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The new Fundamental Law was enacted to institute promises of the October Manifesto as well as add new reforms.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Tsar was confirmed as absolute leader, with complete control of the executive, foreign policy, church, and the armed forces.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The structure of the Duma was changed, becoming a lower chamber below the Council of Ministers, and was half-elected, half-appointed by the Tsar.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Legislations had to be approved by the Duma, the council, and the Tsar to become law.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Fundamental State Laws were the "culmination of the whole sequence of events set in motion in October 1905 and which consolidated the new *status quo*".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The introduction of The Russian Constitution of 1906 was not simply an institution of the October Manifesto.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Constitution did not mention any of the provisions of the October Manifesto.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] While it did enact the provisions laid out previously, its sole purpose seems again to be the propaganda for the monarchy and to simply not fall back on prior promises.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The provisions and the new constitutional monarchy did not satisfy Russians and Lenin.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The Constitution lasted until the fall of the empire in 1917.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] The years 1906 and 1907 saw a decline of mass movements, strikes and protests, and a rise of overt political violence.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Combat groups such as the SR Combat Organization carried out many assassinations targeting civil servants and police, and robberies.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p01] Between 1906 and 1909, revolutionaries killed 7,293 people, of whom 2,640 were officials, and wounded 8,061.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The years of revolution were marked by a dramatic rise in the numbers of death sentences and executions.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Different figures on the number of executions were compared by Senator Nikolai Tagantsev, and are listed in the table.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] These numbers reflect only executions of civilians, and do not include a large number of summary executions by punitive army detachments and executions of military mutineers.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Peter Kropotkin, an anarchist, noted that official statistics excluded executions conducted during punitive expeditions, especially in Siberia, Caucasus and the Baltic provinces.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] By 1906 some 4,509 political prisoners were incarcerated in Russian Poland, 20 percent of the empire's total.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Ivanovo Voznesensk was known as the 'Russian Manchester' for its textile mills.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] In 1905, its local revolutionaries were overwhelmingly Bolshevik.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] It was the first Bolshevik branch in which workers outnumbered intellectuals.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The 1905–1907 revolution was at the time the largest wave of strikes and widest emancipatory movement Poland had ever seen, and it would remain so until the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] In 1905, 93.2% of Congress Poland's industrial workers went on strike.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The first phase of the revolution consisted primarily of mass strikes, rallies, demonstrations—later this evolved into street skirmishes with the police and army as well as bomb assassinations and robberies of transports carrying money to tsarist financial institutions.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] One of the major events of that period was the insurrection in Łódź in June 1905, but unrest happened in many other areas too.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Warsaw was also an active centre of resistance, particularly in terms of strikes, whereas further south the *Republika Ostrowiecka* and *Republika Zagłębiowska* were proclaimed (tsarist control was later restored in these areas when martial law was introduced).
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Due to its reach, violence, radicalism, and effects, some Polish historians even consider the events of the 1905 revolution in Poland a fourth Polish uprising against the Russian Empire.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Rosa Luxemburg described Poland as "one of the most explosive centres of the revolutionary movement" which "in 1905 marched at the head of the Russian Revolution".
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] In the Grand Duchy of Finland, the Social Democrats organised the general strike of 1905 (30 October – 6 November [O.S.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The Red Guards were formed, led by captain Johan Kock.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] During the general strike, the *Red Declaration*, written by Finnish politician and journalist Yrjö Mäkelin, was published in *Tampere,* demanding dissolution of the Senate of Finland, universal suffrage, political freedoms, and abolition of censorship.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Leo Mechelin, leader of the constitutionalists, crafted the *November Manifesto*: the revolution resulted in the abolition of the Diet of Finland and of the four Estates, and to the creation of the modern Parliament of Finland.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] It also resulted in a temporary halt to the Russification policy that Russia had started in 1899.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] 17 July] 1906, Russian artillerymen and military engineers rose in revolt in the fortress of Sveaborg (later called Suomenlinna), Helsinki.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The Finnish Red Guards supported the Sveaborg Rebellion with a general strike, but the mutiny was quelled within 60 hours by loyal troops and ships of the Baltic Fleet.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] In the Governorate of Estonia, Estonians called for freedom of the press and assembly, for universal suffrage, and for national autonomy.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] 16 October], the Russian army opened fire in a meeting on a street market in Tallinn in which about 8 000–10 000 people participated, killing 94 and injuring over 200.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The October Manifesto was supported in Estonia and the Estonian flag was displayed publicly for the first time.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Jaan Tõnisson used the new political freedoms to widen the rights of Estonians by establishing the first Estonian political party – *National Progress Party*.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Another, more radical political organisation, the *Estonian Social Democratic Workers' Union* was founded as well.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The moderate supporters of Tõnisson and the more radical supporters of Jaan Teemant could not agree about how to continue with the revolution, and only agreed that both wanted to limit the rights of Baltic Germans and to end Russification.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The radical views were publicly welcomed and in December 1905, martial law was declared in Tallinn.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] A total of 160 manors were looted, resulting in ca.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] 400 workers and peasants being killed by the army.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Estonian gains from the revolution were minimal, but the tense stability that prevailed between 1905 and 1917 allowed Estonians to advance the aspiration of national statehood.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Following the shooting of demonstrators in St.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Petersburg, a wide-scale general strike began in Riga.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] 13 January], Russian army troops opened fire on demonstrators killing 73 and injuring 200 people.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] During the middle of 1905, the focus of revolutionary events moved to the countryside with mass meetings and demonstrations.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] 470 new parish administrative bodies were elected in 94% of the parishes in Latvia.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] The Congress of Parish Representatives was held in Riga in November.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] In autumn 1905, armed conflict between the Baltic German nobility and the Latvian peasants began in the rural areas of Livonia and Courland.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] In Courland, the peasants seized or surrounded several towns.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] In Livonia, the fighters controlled the Rūjiena-Pärnu railway line.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Martial law was declared in Courland in August 1905, and in Livonia in late November.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Special punitive expeditions were dispatched in mid-December to suppress the movement.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] They executed 1170 people without trial or investigation and burned 300 peasant homes.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] Many Latvian intellectuals only escaped by fleeing to Western Europe or US.
[src:world-war-i/1905-russian-revolution-p02] In 1906, the revolutionary movement gradually subsided.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After receiving the permission of Sultan Mehmed V to form a new government in late October 1912, Kâmil Pasha sat down to engage in diplomatic talks with Bulgaria after the unsuccessful First Balkan War.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] With the Bulgarian demand for the cession of the former Ottoman capital city of Adrianople (today, and in Turkish at the time, known as Edirne) looming and the outrage among the Turkish populace as well as the CUP leadership, the CUP carried out the coup on January 23, 1913.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the coup, opposition parties were subject to heavy repression.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The new government led by Mahmud Şevket Pasha with Unionist support withdrew the Ottoman Empire from the ongoing London Peace Conference and resumed the war against the Balkan states to recover Edirne and the rest of Rumelia, but to no avail.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After his assassination in June, the CUP would take full control of the empire, and opposition leaders would be arrested or exiled to Europe.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The coup occurred in the context of toxic partisanship in the Ottoman Empire between the CUP and the Freedom and Accord Party, coming after a fraudulent general election and another coup the year before.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] During the coup, the Minister of War, Nazım Pasha, was killed and the Grand Vizier, Kâmil Pasha, was forced to resign.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The government fell into the hands of the CUP, now under the leadership of the triumvirate known as the "Three Pashas", made up of Enver, Talât, and Cemal Pasha.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Ottoman victory in the Second Balkan War and the recovery of Edirne in the face of pressure by the Entente powers moved the CUP closer to Germany ahead of World War I.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] In the 1908 elections, the Committee of Union and Progress (CUP) had only managed to win about 60 of the 288 seats in the Chamber of Deputies (Turkish: *Meclis-i Mebusân*), the popularly elected lower house of the General Assembly.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Nevertheless, it was the largest party in the Chamber.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Freedom and Accord Party (Liberal Union/Entente) was founded on 21 November 1911 by those in opposition to the CUP, and immediately attracted 70 Deputies to its ranks.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Only 20 days after its formation, Freedom and Accord won the December 1911 by-elections conducted in Constantinople by one vote.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The ruling CUP, seeing the potential of Freedom and Accord to win next year's general elections, took several precautions.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Hoping to thwart the nascent party's efforts to grow its ranks and better organize itself, the CUP asked Sultan Mehmed V to dissolve the Chamber and announced its call for early general elections in January 1912.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The fraud included early balloting, secret counting and reporting of votes, ballot stuffing, reapportioning electoral districts, and more, although the CUP still enjoyed genuine support outside of the cities.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The results of the elections had CUP win 269 of 275 seats in the Chamber, with Freedom and Accord only netting 6 Deputies.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Angered at their loss in the election, the leadership of Freedom and Accord sought extra-legal methods to regain power over the CUP, complaining vocally about electoral fraud.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At around this time, a group of military officers, uncomfortable with injustices it perceived within the military, organized itself into an armed organization known as the "Savior Officers" (Turkish: *Halâskâr Zâbitân*) and made their presence known to the imperial government.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Savior Officers, quickly becoming partisans of Freedom and Accord, soon created unrest in the capital Constantinople.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After gaining the support of Prince Sabahaddin, another opposition leader, the Savior Officers published public declarations in newspapers.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Finally, after giving a memorandum to the Military Council, the Savior Officers succeeded in getting Grand Vizier Mehmed Said Pasha (who they blamed for allowing the early elections that led to the CUP domination of the Chamber) and his government of CUP ministers to resign in July 1912.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although the Savior Officers had succeeded in making sure that the Great Cabinet was free of CUP members, the CUP's domination of the Chamber of Deputies had not changed.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Soon, however, rumors began to circulate that the government would dissolve the Chamber of Deputies and call new elections.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The rumors were confirmed when, a few days after Ahmed Muhtar Pasha took office, the Savior Officers sent another memorandum, this time to the President of the Chamber of Deputies (and CUP member), Halil Bey, demanding that the Chamber be dissolved for new elections within 48 hours.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The CUP members in the Chamber condemned and censured this threat.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] However, thanks to a law he had passed through the Senate, Ahmed Muhtar Pasha was able, with the sultan's support, to dissolve the Chamber with ease on 5 August, after which Sultan Mehmed V immediately called for new elections by imperial decree.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] While preparations for new elections were underway, however, the First Balkan War erupted early in October 1912, catching Ahmed Muhtar Pasha's administration off-guard.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although the foreign crisis in the Balkans put a temporary halt to domestic politics, it did not stop them.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Unlike his predecessor Ahmed Muhtar Pasha, who had been non-partisan, Kâmil Pasha was an ardent anti-Unionist and was determined to use his premiership to destroy the CUP.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After 1 January 1913 when the party came under the control of Gümülcineli İsmail, he saw both the CUP and Freedom and Accord as dangerous revolutionary committees.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Using his friendly relations with the British, Kâmil Pasha also sat down to end the ongoing First Balkan War diplomatically.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] However, the heavy Ottoman military defeats during the war continued to sap morale, as rumors that the capital would have to be moved from Constantinople to inland Anatolia spread.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Bulgarian Army had soon advanced as far as Çatalca, a western district of modern Istanbul.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At this point, Kâmil Pasha's government signed an armistice with Bulgaria in December 1912 and sat down to draw up a treaty for the end of the war at the London Peace Conference.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Great Powers–the British Empire, France, Italy, and Russia–had begun to engage in the relationship of Bulgaria with the Ottoman Empire, citing the 1878 Treaty of Berlin.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Great Powers gave a note to the Sublime Porte (the Ottoman government) that they wanted the Ottoman Empire to cede Adrianople (Edirne) to Bulgaria and the Aegean islands under its control, most of which by that time had been captured by the Greek Navy, to the Great Powers themselves.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Because of the losses experienced by the army so far in the war, the Kâmil Pasha government was inclined to accept the "Midye-Enez Line" as a border to the west and, while not outright giving Edirne to Bulgaria, favored transferring control of it to an international commission.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the capture of Salonica (Thessaloniki), the birthplace of many progressive political leaders and movements of the era, by Greece in November 1912, many CUP members were arrested by Greek forces and exiled to Anatolia.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At the same time, Freedom and Accord found itself on the brink of dissolution after intra-party conflicts.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Left with little political power and flexibility, the CUP began to plan a coup against Kâmil Pasha's government.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] In addition, an animosity had already been brewing between Kâmil Pasha and the CUP since the 1908 Young Turk Revolution that had started the Second Constitutional Era.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] During the more than four years since, Kâmil Pasha had made a series of efforts to keep CUP members far from government and keep the army, which had many CUP members among its ranks, out of politics.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] By January 1913, the CUP was thoroughly frustrated with Kâmil Pasha.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although the coup was to be a surprise attack, the CUP had made definitive decisions to carry it out far in advance.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although he was killed during the coup, both the CUP and Freedom and Accord claimed that they had been planning to give Minister of the Navy Nazım Pasha a position in their next cabinet.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The CUP's Talaat Bey went as far as to say some time after the coup that the CUP had previously offered Nazım Pasha the position of grand vizier and the leadership its cabinet.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At this time, Talaat Bey (later known as Talaat Pasha) also began to make his way towards the Sublime Porte with a group of CUP loyalists.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] When Enver Bey arrived in front of the Ministry of Public Works (Turkish: *Nafıa Nazırlığı*) building, fellow CUP members Ömer Naci and Ömer Seyfettin were already provoking a crowd that had gathered by loudly proclaiming that Kâmil Pasha was about to cede Adrianople to the Bulgarians.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The speeches made by Ömer Naci and Ömer Seyfettin were effective, and the front of the Sublime Porte was soon filled with a crowd shouting slogans against Kâmil Pasha's government.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Moreover, up to 60 CUP members were placed around the Sublime Porte's buildings.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Enver Bey, along with confederates Talaat Bey, Sapancalı Hakkı, Yakub Cemil, Mustafa Necip, and about 50 others, entered the Sublime Porte compound of government buildings and made their way into the Grand Vizier's building, in which Kâmil Pasha and his cabinet were in session.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] An aide-de-camp to the Grand Vizier, Ohrili Nâfiz Bey, heard the commotion and opened fire on the raid party but was unable to hit any of them.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Himself wounded in the exchange, Ohrili Nâfiz Bey hid in the aide-de-camp office; when Mustafa Necip entered the office, Ohrili Nâfiz Bey shot and killed him but died himself of his wounds sustained from Mustafa Necip.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] An aid-de-camp and nephew of Nazım Pasha, Kıbrıslı Tevfik Bey, had also drawn his revolver and fired at the raid party, his bullet also striking Mustafa Necip.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the raiders returned fire, Kıbrıslı Tevfik Bey was instantly killed.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] During the shooting, a secret police agent and an attendant of the Sheikh ul-Islam were also killed.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Hearing the gunshots, Minister of War Nazım Pasha stepped out of his room and rushed towards the raid party.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] According to the memoirs of future Turkish president and prime minister Celâl Bayar, Nazım Pasha angrily shouted at the men, "What is going on?
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] You came to raid the grand vizier's office?", using "ill-mannered" profanities in his rage, after which Enver Bey saluted him and tried to explain his intentions.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] At this time Yakub Cemil, approaching Nazım Pasha from the back while he was engaged with Enver Bey and the rest of the coup party, fired his gun at Nazım Pasha's right temple, killing him.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Another account claimed that Enver Bey had tried to stop Yakup Cemil from killing Nazım Pasha, but Yakup Cemil had refused to listen.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Yet another version of events held that either Enver Bey or Talaat Bey had accidentally killed Nazım Pasha while trying to protect themselves from gunfire from his aid-de-camp Kıbrıslı Tevfik Bey.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] In any case, the CUP termed Nazım Pasha's death during the coup a "regrettable accident", saying that it was unpremeditated but "unavoidable" under the circumstances.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The CUP said that the fact Interior Minister Ahmet Reşit had been allowed to go unhurt proved that the coup leaders had desired to avoid bloodshed, since Ahmet Reşit was much more hostile towards the CUP than Nazım Pasha was.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After this, Enver and Talaat Bey entered Grand Vizier Kâmil Pasha's room and forced him to write a letter of resignation at gunpoint.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After Kâmil Pasha finished writing, Enver Bey immediately left the Sublime Porte to deliver the letter to Sultan Mehmed V in his palace, driving to the palace in the Sheikh ul-Islam's (Şeyhülislam) car.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Kâmil Pasha was replaced as Grand Vizier and Nazım Pasha as Minister of War by Mahmud Shevket Pasha, who took both posts.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Although the CUP appointed Grand Vizier Mahmud Shevket Pasha to lead their cabinet, he was genial towards the opposition Freedom and Accord Party.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] When one of Nazım Pasha's relatives assassinated him in revenge in June 1913, the CUP used the opportunity to crack down on the opposition.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Twelve men held responsible by the CUP for Mahmud Shevket Pasha's death, including Nazım Pasha's relative, were convicted for murder and hanged.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The opposition parties, already sidelined by the coup, were heavily repressed by the CUP.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The leaders of the Savior Officers (Turkish: *Halâskâr Zâbitân*) escaped to Egypt and Albania.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Another opposition leader Prince Sabahaddin, who had backed the Savior Officers against the CUP, fled to western Switzerland, where he would remain until 1919.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Freedom and Accord partisans would attempt several plots against the Unionist government until the outbreak of World War I.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The party would regain some semblance of power in the Armistice Era after World War I, though again fell into infighting under Colonel Sadık's chairmanship.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The coup essentially led to the establishment of a dictatorial triumvirate known as the "Three Pashas": the soon-to-be war minister, Enver Pasha, the soon-to-be interior minister, Talaat Pasha, and the soon-to-be naval minister, Cemal Pasha.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The Three Pashas, leading the CUP autocratically, would control the Empire until fleeing the country at the end of World War I.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The coup is considered one of the first violent coups d'état to take place in modern Turkish history, seen as some as establishing a precedent for future coups in the Republic of Turkey.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Though initially opposed in principle to the extension of local autonomy to the provinces, the CUP now seemed inclined to reconcile with those in favor of greater extension of the millet system to enable Ottoman Muslim unity.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The CUP government introduced several political and military reforms to the empire, including increasing centralization and carrying out military modernization efforts.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Under coup leader Enver Bey (later Pasha), the Ottoman Empire moved towards a closer relationship with the German Empire, officially leading to the German–Ottoman alliance being ratified the next year in 1914.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Enver would enter the empire into World War I that same year as part of the Central Powers, on the side of Germany, in contrast to the overthrown Kâmil Pasha, who was partial towards the British.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The first major offensive the Turks undertook in World War I was an unsuccessful attempt to drive the Russians from the portion of Western Armenia they had taken in the Russo-Turkish War of 1877.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the failure of this expedition, the CUP's leaders, Enver, Cemal, and Talaat, were involved in ordering the deportations and massacres of 1 and 1.5 million Armenians in 1915–1916 in what became known as the Armenian genocide.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After World War I and the signing of the armistice of Mudros, the leadership of the Committee of Union and Progress and selected former officials were court-martialled with/including the charges of subversion of the constitution, wartime profiteering, and the massacres of both Armenians and Greeks.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The court reached a verdict which sentenced the organizers of the massacres, Talat, Enver, Cemal and others to death.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] The public support for the coup was questioned at the time by analysts, some of whom reported that the CUP was backed by only a small crowd of actual citizens who had been gathered only within the hour by provocative speeches made by CUP members.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Eyewitnesses and newspapers reported very little actual popular participation in the coup or the events surrounding it.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] Rémond said that preventing the minimalist coup would have taken at most 50 guards, and that the only reason that the Sublime Porte had been defenseless was because Kâmil Pasha wanted to call the bluff of any real threat the CUP, which he had sidelined politically, posed to his government.
[src:world-war-i/1913-ottoman-coup-d-état] After the coup, Rémond said, he found the capital Constantinople to be quiet and devoid of public opinion, whether about the coup or the ongoing First Balkan War, noting an air of "indifference" among not only the populace, but the statesmen involved themselves.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] The **1913 Romanian Army cholera outbreak** was a cholera outbreak the Romanian Army suffered during the Second Balkan War of 1913 against the Kingdom of Bulgaria.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] This conflict was part of the Balkan Wars of 1912 and 1913.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] As Bulgaria was then fighting with Greece and Serbia, the invasion by Romania, which had a geographic and strategic advantage, was met with minimal Bulgarian resistance.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] The Romanian Army had to operate in a battleground with a low infrastructure and under the weather conditions of the summer.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] Furthermore, the little organization of the army's services provoked deficiencies in the alimentary and sanitary conditions of the Romanian soldiers.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] These conditions facilitated the spread of cholera.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] Thus, the first case of an infected Romanian soldier occurred on 13 July 1913.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] A week later, on 20 July, the cases were 2,000.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] This number rose so quickly due to ignorance of Romanian army officers, who ignored and even ridiculed the warnings by the army's physicians on several occasions.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] It was quickly determined that vaccination had to begin, this happening on 22 July.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] Medical measures were quickly taken to curb the epidemic.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] The Romanian physician Ioan Cantacuzino began several series of inoculations of Romanian soldiers, and after the third one in 3 August, the cases were drastically reduced.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] Thanks to all this, the last case of cholera occurred in November and the disease could be mostly stopped before the Romanian soldiers returned to Romania.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] Marie of Romania, Princess and future Queen of Romania, organized a system of treatment and quarantine for the Romanian soldiers when they arrived, avoiding a possible spread of cholera among Romanian civilians.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] Although figures might be conflicting, out of the approximately 400,000 Romanian soldiers who entered Bulgaria during the war, it is estimated that there may have been some 11,500–15,000 infected and a total of 1,600 dead.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] This made all Romanian casualties during the Second Balkan War non-military related, only caused by the cholera outbreak.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] Romania accused the local Bulgarian population and Turkish prisoners of war for the cholera outbreak, while Bulgaria blamed the Romanian Army and its "poor hygiene conditions".
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] Once the Second Balkan War ended and after the Treaty of Bucharest was signed, Romania gained Southern Dobruja from Bulgaria.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] A few years later, Romania itself suffered numerous cases of cholera as a result of its participation in the First World War.
[src:world-war-i/1913-romanian-army-cholera-outbreak] To treat them, Queen Marie of Romania applied the same procedures as in the 1913 epidemic.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The **1914** **French mobilization** was the set of operations at the very start of World War I that put the French Army and Navy in a position for war, including the theoretical call to arms of all Frenchmen fit for military service.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Planned long before 1914 (via Plan XVII), each man's assignment was based on his age and residence.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Such event had political (Sacred Union), socio-economic (due to the departure of almost all young men) and, of course, military consequences (the start of the Battle of the Frontiers).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] It was the first time that a general mobilization was declared in France (in 1870, only the professional army was mobilized); the second took place in 1939.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] In August 1914, 3,780,000 men were mobilized; in total, throughout the war, some 8,410,000 French soldiers and sailors were mobilized, including 7% indigenous soldiers.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The Industrial Revolution transformed the art of warfare, not only through the development of weapons and equipment, but above all through the ability of states to effectively mobilize armies with million of men.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Since it was economically and socially impossible to keep them all permanently in uniform, they were left to live civilian lives during peacetime, and states mobilized them in the event of conflict, hoping to keep it short.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Only a small proportion of its units were fully composed of professional soldiers (notably some of the colonial troops and the Foreign Legion).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] By 1913, 221 provincial towns had garrisons, making uniforms a common sight on the streets, with parades, retreats (evening marches through the streets), military music and more.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Service was reduced from five to three years by the law of July 15, 1889 (or the Freycinet law).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] This situation was reformed by the law of March 21, 1905 (or the Berteaux law), which abolished the drawing of lots, replacements and exemptions: henceforth, all men could be called up for two years.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Finally, the law of August 7, 1913 (or the Barthou law) increased military service from two to three years.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] For the eleven years following his service, men were assigned to the military reserve force (from age 24 to 34), then to the Territorial Army for seven years (from age 35 to 41), and finally to the Territorial Army Reserve for another seven years (from age 42 to 48).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Men doing their service were transferred to active regiments, theoretically recruited locally; after their service, they were called up three times for maneuvers and exercises, two times for reservists (each one for four weeks) and one time for territorial army reservists (of only two weeks).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] In theory, men declared unfit for service due to physical incapacity were still subject to military obligations, in the form of auxiliary service (in offices, depots, the health service, etc.).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] A final case is that of the "special assigned", i.e. customs officers, forest hunters, men in field railway sections, and post and telegraph officers.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Each year, a "class" of conscripts was recruited: a class is a group of men born in the same year and fit for service.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The number of a class corresponds to the year of its census, generally taken in December of the year in which they turned twenty; conscription took place the year after the census, in autumn.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] When mobilized, men from the active forces and the youngest reservists formed the units sent into combat, while older reservists were destined to form reserve regiments kept behind the front or to fill depots while waiting to replace casualties.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The men of the territorial army formed units for tasks behind the front, such as the garrisoning of squares or entrenchment work.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Finally, men from the Territorial Army Reserve were to be used to guard railroads and the coast.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The French Navy recruited its personnel in a different way, based on maritime recruitment: men engaged in maritime or river navigation were required to serve in the "army of the sea", with a five-year term of service in peacetime.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] However, as the fleet needed a large number of qualified technicians, recruitment was nationwide, with maritime enrollment providing only half of the fleet's manpower in the event of mobilization.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The plan applied in 1914 was Plan XVII, prepared in 1913 by the General Staff and validated by the Superior War Council.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] It provided for the mobilization of men, their concentration on the borders, their organization into several armies and the direction of the first offensives.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] But as all this would take around a fortnight, some of the active troops also needed to cover this mobilization.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The role entrusted to the navy, which was outclassed by the German navy, was simply to protect troop convoys from Algeria and Morocco (in the hope that Italy would be neutral) and to block the English Channel to German ships (in the hope of British support).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] In the event of partial mobilization (motivated by the "threat of aggression characterized by the gathering of armed foreign forces"), only the two youngest reserve units were called up.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] In the event of general mobilization, everyone was called up, without any individual notification.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Each infantry depot completes an active regiment (with three battalions), increasing it from 2,000 men to just over 3,200, then sets up a reserve regiment (with two battalions, numbered 5 and 6), followed by a territorial regiment.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Finally the guard posts for communication routes (railroads, canals, telephone and telegraph lines).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Each cavalry depot reinforces its cavalry regiment with two reserve squadrons; each artillery depot completes its artillery regiment and creates a reserve group (composed of several batteries); each engineer depot reinforces its regiment with new companies.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] A few hundred reservists are maintained in each depot to replace future losses.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The vote by the Chamber of Deputies on the Law of Three Years in 1913 was requested by the Army Staff, which wanted to have as many active units as its German counterpart, the *Deutsches Heer* (for fear of a possible sudden attack).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Thanks to this law, the peacetime army grew from 520,000 to 736,000 men in uniform, each company from 90 to 140 men, with ten new infantry regiments (nos.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] This force was structured into 22 corps, each assigned to a military region (or "corps region": in 1914 there were twenty in Metropolitan France, plus one in Algeria).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Between 1914 and 1918, the core tactical element was the infantry division.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] On August 2, 1914, France mobilized 93 divisions, including 45 active, 25 reserve, 11 territorial, 2 colonial and 10 cavalry divisions.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] By November 11, 1918, France had 119 infantry divisions.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Mobilization was determined by rail resources and by the strategy planned for the start of the conflict.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] These trains were made up of 34 (for a squadron) to 47 (for a battalion) wagons, making for 400-meter-long convoys, with passenger carriages, goods wagons (at a rate of eight horses or forty men per wagon) and flat wagons (for vans and cannons), as required.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] As a result, railroads were extensively developed for military reasons, each subprefecture was connected (Freycinet plan from 1879 to 1914), double tracks led eastwards (notably those from Paris to Nancy and Paris to Belfort) with ring roads between them, while some stations were enlarged (e.g.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Overseas troops were a special case: the 19th Army Corps (mainly recruited and stationed in Algeria) had to supply two divisions (the 37th and 38th), which had to cross the Mediterranean on requisitioned ships and under the protection of French squadrons to land at Sète and Marseille.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Colonial troops in the colonies were not included in the mobilization and concentration plan.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Troops were stationed directly along the Franco-German border to protect mobilization from the very first day, relying on fortifications in the East.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Their mission under the XVII plan was "initially, to stop enemy reconnaissance or detachments seeking to penetrate the territory, and subsequently, to delay the march of larger corps that could disrupt the landing and concentration of armies".
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] These corps were theoretically available in two echelons: the first between the 3rd and 8th hour of mobilization, the second from the 2nd to the 4th day; the 12th Reims division was to serve as reserve.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Relations between Germany and France at the start of the 20th century were marked by a series of diplomatic tensions, most notably the two Moroccan crises: the Tangier crisis of 1905 and the Agadir crisis of 1911.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] However, it was through the alliances that these two states were forced to declare their mobilization.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The *casus belli* of the Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinandt triggered a succession of ultimatums, mobilizations and declarations of war that quickly spread to Germany and then France.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] On July 25, 1914, the Kingdom of Serbia decreed its mobilization in response to the Austro-Hungarian ultimatum; on the same day, Austria-Hungary announced partial mobilization from the 28th.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] On the 29th, the Russian Empire followed with a partial mobilization due to start on July 30.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] On the 30th, the Tsar ordered general mobilization, which had no other consequences than the inevitable Austrian (from the 31st) and German mobilizations.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] In France, at 7 a.m. on July 30, Chief of Staff Joffre asked War Minister Messimy for an order to mobilize, or at least to cover the borders, but did not receive it.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] At 7 p.m., the German ambassador to France, Schoen, met the President of the Council, Viviani, and under the orders of the German Chancellor asked him whether France would remain neutral in the event of a Russo-German war: the Frenchman procrastinated ("allow me time to think").
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] At 11 a.m. on August 1, Schoen met Viviani again to obtain the reply that "France will be guided by its interests".
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] At 3:45 p.m., the French government decreed the start of general mobilization on August 2.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Kaiser Wilhelm II ordered the German mobilization, then declared war on Russia at 7 p.m.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] On the evening of the 2nd, Germany told the Belgian government not to oppose the passage of German troops through Belgium.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] On the 3rd, the German ambassador transmitted the declaration of war to France to the head of the French government at 6:45 p.m.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] (on the basis that French aircraft had attacked German territory) and left Paris, while Belgium refused to let German troops through.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The mobilization order was issued by the "Decree ordering the mobilization of the Army and Navy on August 1, 1914", published in the *Journal Officiel* on August 2.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The first poster was put up on August 1 at 4pm on the corner of Concorde and Rue Royale.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The entire population was informed on the same day by posters, printed since 1904 (only the date needed to be completed), posted on public roads in each commune and then by the tocsin sounded by church and belfry bells.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Similarly, in Nyons, a town in the Drôme region, a schoolteacher testifies: "The population, although prepared for the war for several days by the press, learned the unfortunate news with a sort of stupor.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Analyzed by Jean-Jacques Becker, these documents show the different stages of popular reaction.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The initial astonishment was often followed by a certain despondency: "consternation, sadness and anguish were widespread, far more so than feelings dictated by the patriotic impulse", and expressions of enthusiasm were rare.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] President Raymond Poincaré's proclamation, posted and published in the newspapers on August 2, was reassuring, emphasizing "mobilization is not war; on the contrary, in the present circumstances, it appears to be the best means of ensuring peace with honor.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The government, strengthened by its ardent desire to reach a peaceful solution to the crisis and shielded by these necessary precautions, will continue its diplomatic efforts and still hopes to succeed.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] It is counting on the composure of the noble nation not to give way to unjustified emotion; it is counting on the patriotism of all Frenchmen, and knows that there is not one who is not ready to do his duty.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] At this hour, there are no more parties, there is an eternal, peaceful and resolute France.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] There is the entire country of law and justice, united in calm, vigilance and dignity".
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] However, the mood had changed by the time the soldiers left for their barracks, as described above in Aignes.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] How can this change in mood be explained?
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] According to Jean-Jacques Becker, revanchist sentiments linked to the 1870 war and the loss of Alsace-Lorraine played little part.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] French public opinion was dominated by the idea of a peaceful France, obliged to defend itself against outright German aggression.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Under these conditions, refusing to fight was out of the question.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Military and political leaders were worried about the possible refusal to obey by civilians called up as reservists: they feared that the number of *insoumis* (deserters) would be significant, and that pacifist demonstrations would take place.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] Several opposition unions and political parties, notably the CGT and SFIO, had taken anti-militarist stances before the crisis broke out, and were planning a general strike (the refusal to obey mobilization orders) to prevent the outbreak of conflict.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] On July 29 and 30, SFIO leader Jean Jaurès was in Brussels for a meeting of the bureau of the Second International and a meeting with German socialist leaders, with the aim of coordinating their pacifist actions.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] However, the surge of patriotism and the assassination of Jaurès in Paris on July 31 led the Left Party to rally to the "Sacred Union" called for by President Poincaré in his speech on August 4.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The CGT announced that it was putting its Paris premises on rue de la Grange-aux-Belles at the disposal of the Army Medical Corps.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] The SFIO voted for the war loans, then joined the government in the reshuffle of August 26, gaining the Ministries of War and Foreign Affairs.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p01] — Raymond Poincaré, Message to the Chambers, read by Prime Minister René Viviani on August 4, 1914.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Not all men were mobilized at the same time, but gradually, depending on their status.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The 200,000 men of the Territorial Reserve assigned to guarding transport routes were mobilized on the eve of the first day of mobilization (i.e.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] August 1), to protect important railroads and engineering structures close to their homes (usually less than ten kilometers away, or 6.2 miles).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The 880,000 men in the active service, i.e. classes 1911, 1912 and 1913 (born between 1891 and 1893, aged 21 to 23) were already in depots and barracks.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Immediately, the railways prepared wagons for troop transport.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The youngest reservists (classes 1910, 1909 and 1908) completed the active units, and must join the depots on the 2nd and 3rd days of mobilization, i.e.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Slightly older reservists (classes 1907, 1906, 1905 and 1904) formed reserve units (supervised by a few officers and men from the active service) and must be present at the depot from the 3rd, 4th or 5th day, depending on the unit, i.e. from Tuesday August 4 or Thursday August 6.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] As for the oldest reservists (classes 1903 and 1902), they must theoretically remain at the depot to replace future losses.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Territorial reservists were called up a little later.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The *École Polytechnique* was also closed for mobilization, and all students from the class of 1913 were transferred to the artillery or engineering corps as sub-lieutenants.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Second-year students at the École navale left with the rank of second petty officer of the fleet, but kept their student uniforms.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The 1st cuirassier regiment was even kept in Paris for three days in the *École Militaire* barracks as a precautionary measure, "for reasons of domestic policy", as reinforcements for the Republican Guard.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] As for rebels and deserters prior to mobilization, they were offered amnesty if they surrendered voluntarily.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] From August 1 to 15, 2,887,000 men were drafted, then 1,099,000 from August 16 to September 30, giving an estimated total of 3,986,000 men (the 1911 census announced a population of 39.7 million in France, including 19.5 million men, of whom 12.6 million were fitted).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] In September and October 1914, all those discharged and exempted from the 1887 to 1914 classes were enumerated and then recalled by the draft boards.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Each man wears around his neck an oval aluminum identity plate (with surname, first name and class on one side, and regional subdivision and regimental number on the other), which is only issued in wartime.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Stores were emptied for reservists, so the territorials were often dressed and equipped with old clothes and old-fashioned weaponry.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] In two weeks, the French army went from 686 to 1,636 infantry battalions, from 365 to 596 cavalry squadrons, from 855 to 1,527 artillery batteries and from 191 to 528 engineer units.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Its structure grew from 54 divisions in metropolitan France (including ten cavalry divisions, not counting units in the French North Africa) in peacetime to 94 divisions (46 active, 25 reserve, 13 territorial and 10 cavalry) standing on the ready.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] In addition, there were 21 army squadrons (each with eight aircraft), two cavalry squadrons, five airships, four companies of local balloonists, and 212 sections of the automotive service (transporting troops, equipment, medical supplies and fresh meat).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Departure for the border was on schedule, with the unit theoretically fully manned and equipped.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] As early as July 25, 1914, all general officers and chefs de corps (unit commanders) were recalled and their leave withdrawn and on the 26th, all units on leave were ordered to return to their barracks.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Then, On the evening of the 27th, troops on leave from the five army corps on the border were recalled, and these corps applied the "*dispositif restreint de sécurité" (*restricted safety system*)* (measures to protect communication routes, especially engineering structures).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] In the middle of the night of the 27th to the 28th, the Ministry of War ordered the recall of those on leave from the interior corps.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On the 29th, the Minister ordered the guarding of fortified structures, military establishments and wireless stations in the six frontier corps (1st in Maubeuge, 2nd in the Ardennes, 6th in Verdun, 20th in Toul, 21st in Épinal and 7th corps in Belfort).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] These covering positions were commanded by generals from the various frontier army corps, under the direct command of the General-in-Chief until the 5th day, when they came under the orders of army commanders.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Ahead of the "big ones" several groups were placed, each composed of a battalion and a squadron, with cavalry "scouts" supported by customs officers and forestry hunters further forward.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Transport of the cover was completed on August 3, thanks to 538 trains; the three early-mobilization divisions were in place by August 5.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The navy was also involved in preventive measures.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] From July 25, leave-holders were recalled, reserve ships were reconditioned, munitions of war began to be loaded and schools closed.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On July 29, the battleships concentrated in Toulon filled up with coal.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On July 31, trawlers were requisitioned (to be used as auxiliary minesweepers) and port defenses were organized.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 2, the general firing order for the ships' boilers (several hours of heating are needed to build up sufficient steam pressure) is given for 10:15 pm.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 3, at 4:50 a.m., the squadrons set sail from Toulon to protect links with North Africa.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The first border incident occurred on the 2nd of August: a German patrol from the Jäger-Regiment zu Pferde Nr.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Further German reconnaissance near Longwy and Lunéville verified the French positions.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On the morning of the 2nd, the Chief of the General Staff sent a note to the Minister of War: "We have had to abandon positions which were of some importance to the development of our campaign plan.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Eventually, we will be obliged to regain these positions, which will not be without sacrifice." Almost immediately, he obtained "absolute freedom of movement to carry out his plans, even if this means crossing the German border".
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 3, Joffre called a meeting of his five army commanders in the offices of the Ministry of War, before leaving for his newly created headquarters in Vitry-le-François.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] This huge move, organized by the General Staff, was made possible by the requisitioning of the railroads (Nord, Est, PO, PLM and Midi), which lost all autonomy (except financial) on the evening of July 31.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] This requisition was total: personnel, installations and all equipment were under army control.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Between August 6 and 18, the concentration of the French army required 4,035 trains running on the ten lines organized by the military.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Local companies were also affected by the requisition.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] There were also wagon fires and a number of accidents: for example, on August 6, a soldier from the 61st infantry regiment in Privas "perched on the brakeman's cab of a wagon hit a structure and was killed outright" before the Givors-Canal station.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 4, the *Kaiserliche* Navy cruisers SMS Goeben and SMS Breslau bombarded Philippeville and Bône, before fleeing as the British ships approached.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The French crossing was uneventful after this surprise, with the two Algerian divisions landing in Sète and Marseille, while the Moroccan division ("*division de marche d'infanterie coloniale du Maroc*") did so in Bordeaux.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] They were then transported by rail, requiring 239 trains.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The transport lines supplied the troops needed to form, from August 5 onwards, the five maneuver armies of Plan XVII, which foresaw a French offensive towards *Elsaß-Lothringen* (German Alsace-Lorraine) and the possibility of a meeting in the Belgian Ardennes.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Only the active divisions were placed in the front line, with the reserve divisions held back until they could be properly taken over and further trained.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The thirteen territorial infantry divisions were the last to be formed, and their concentration continued until August 19.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The last four divisions, the 83rd, 85th, 86th and 89th, were garrisoned in the entrenched camp of Paris, with limited means of transport, hence their name of "territorial site divisions".
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] As Italian and Spanish neutrality was confirmed at the beginning of August, and the British entry into the war secured the coasts, the field divisions were reassigned to the Northeast, with the exception of the 90th, which was sent to North Africa from August 12.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The announcement that German troops had entered Luxembourg on the morning of August 2 confirmed to the French General Staff the hypothesis of a German attack attempting to overrun the French concentration by flanking through Belgium (invaded from the morning of August 4).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] In addition to the French Army's battle corps, the British Expeditionary Force (commanded by Field Marshal John French: four infantry divisions and one cavalry division) was secretly foreseen in the French concentration plan.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The British decision to send their small army to France was taken on August 5, 1914; and the decision to deploy it at Maubeuge only on August 9 (Secretary of State for War Kitchener preferred Amiens).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] From August 9 onwards, the various units were embarked in Southampton, Cork, Dublin and Belfast, arriving until August 17 in Le Havre, Rouen and Boulogne, before being transported (by the W railroad line, created for it) and deployed near Maubeuge, at the left end of the French line.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] A "*state de siège*" (state of emergency) was declared on August 2, 1914 (two days before receiving the German declaration of war) in all French departments (including Algeria) and maintained for the duration of the war.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Mayors and prefects immediately lost their police powers to the military authorities, allowing the army to ban meetings, search homes and bring civilians before military tribunals (with highly simplified procedures and immediate execution of sentences).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] However, the General Headquarters remained accountable to the executive, which in turn was accountable to Parliament, for the duration of the state of siege - which was not lifted until November 1919, more than a year after the armistice.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] German and Austro-Hungarian residents were evacuated from the North-East and from the strongholds; all foreigners were required to have a residence permit.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Elections were suspended, as the majority of the electorate, including several deputies, were in uniform (women and soldiers did not have the right to vote under the Third Republic) and part of the country was occupied.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 2, the Senate and Chamber of Deputies were called into extraordinary session from the 4th to vote on a series of emergency laws.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] From July 31, the French government took a series of economic decisions to accompany its entry into the war.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The export of products that could be used for military purposes was prohibited: arms, munitions and explosives, of course, but also livestock, horses, canned goods, meat, flour, hides, fodder, hay, straw, aeroplanes, aerostats, cars, tires, camping gear, lead, etc.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The budget allocated to the Ministry of War was increased by a credit of 208 million francs, covering new expenditure on barracks, remounting, clothing, bedding, furnishings, camping, health equipment, armaments and fortifications.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] To ensure the administration's workload, some civil servants were left on call, and those mobilized were gradually replaced by retired volunteers (later by women and the disabled).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Pigeons were kept under surveillance (civilians were forbidden to move or import pigeons).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Mass mobilization had immediate economic and social consequences: young adult men and horses (around 135,000 horses in August, 600,000 throughout the war, aged between five and fifteen, as well as mules and donkeys) left for the frontiers, completely disrupting the economy and society.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Businesses slowed down or closed temporarily.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Passenger rail traffic was almost totally interrupted during the period of concentration, limited to lines not used by the army.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] In Montbéliard on August 5, all non-mobilized workers aged 16 to 60 were called by the municipality to work on fortifications at Fort Lachaux.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Under the law of August 5, 1914, a daily allowance of one franc and 25 centimes per day was paid to poor families whose "provider" was mobilized.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Fearing a shortage of bread, reserve bakers were granted a 45-day deferment of call-up at the request of mayors, and on August 8 bakery production was limited to a four-pound loaf, while brioches, croissants and pastries were banned.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 13, the government ordered the deferment of rents for the duration of the war.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] — René Viviani, ('Appel aux femmes françaises') Call to French women, poster, August 2, 1914.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Some harvesting and haymaking is still to be done (early August), while the grape harvest is still to come (September and October), and industry has to supply clothing, equipment, weapons and ammunition to the army.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The mobilization plan left only 50,000 workers in armaments factories (powder works, artillery arsenals and thirty private suppliers), with rare call-up deferrals and partial replacement of mobilized workers by auxiliaries and non-mobilizables; other industrial sectors temporarily ceased operations.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] To feed the troops in the short term, the military authorities requisitioned flour, livestock and wine.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] From the end of 1914 onwards, solutions included recalling skilled workers to the rear ("*affectés spéciaux*", or special assigned), using female workers ("munitionnettes"), children, foreigners (notably Africans and Chinese), prisoners of war and the disabled.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The main consequences were military: general mobilization provided the French army with the manpower it needed to wage war against Germany and the other Central Powers.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 4, covering troops seized the Vosges passes of La Schlucht (two hours after receiving notification of the declaration of war), Bussang and Oderen.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 6, the cavalry corps entered Belgium via Bouillon, Bertrix and Paliseul.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 7, the French 7th Corps crossed the border into Germany and began the conquest of Haute-Alsace.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] On August 14, all units of the 1st and 2nd Armies entered Moselle, while the 3rd, 4th and 5th Armies awaited the Germans along the Ardennes section of the Meuse.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] For the French navy, the entry of the British into the war meant that it no longer had to fear the German navy.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] As the Lorient fusiliers marins depot was full, and no landings were initially planned, on August 7 these troops, together with detachments from all the ports, formed two regiments grouped together in a fusiliers marins brigade (6,400 men, led by naval and marine officers).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] This brigade, commanded by Rear Admiral Ronarc'h, was sent to the stronghold of Paris from August 17, before being sent to the front on October 7.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] These "rookies" first had to complete their training before going into battle; the class of 1919 was only at the front during the last weeks of the war (this was the case for the "last poilus" Fernand Goux and Pierre Picault).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Even imprisoned criminals and ex-convicts were drafted into the Battalions of Light Infantry of Africa.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] In total, all colonies combined, 583,450 men were gradually drafted, leading to several uprisings in the colonies.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The first estimate of the total number of men mobilized during the conflict was published in 1920 by MP Louis Marin (who, as budget recorder, needed to know how many families needed to be compensated), based on a report from the Army Staff.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Among these, 1,329,640 died as a result of the fighting, to which must be added around three million wounded (including 700,000 disabled).
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Right from the start of the Great War, the main subject of historical research was not mobilization itself, but the causes and, above all, the people responsible for the conflict.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The first historian to really look into the subject of mobilization was Charles Petit-Dutaillis, medievalist and rector of the Grenoble academy in 1914, who ordered all teachers in the Isère, Drôme and Hautes-Alpes regions to report on the attitude of the local population in the early days.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] This rector's initiative was passed on to the Minister of Public Instruction, Albert Sarraut, who decided to send out a circular dated September 18, 1914, instructing all non-mobilized teachers to keep notes on war-related events, starting with mobilization.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] During and after the conflict, it was the diplomatic aspects (always linked to the question of responsibilities) and military aspects (essentially operations) that dominated historical production, with the work of Pierre Renouvin in particular.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The success of this mythical vision of the French entry into the war can be explained by three factors.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The first was the immediate usefulness of a mobilization that was presented as enthusiastic, and which was the popular equivalent of the Sacred Union, both of which seemed to emanate from the people as a whole, whereas they were merely the fruit of circumstance.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Secondly, the images conveyed by the press and the writings of intellectuals exalting the war contributed powerfully to forging this myth of the flower in the gun.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Finally, this representation makes it possible to transfer responsibility for the conflict onto the political leaders, with the crowds letting themselves be carried away by their naivety, without there being any question of their consenting to the war.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] In the early 1960s, Jean-Jacques Becker made the study of public opinion at the time of the French entry into the war the subject of his thesis, supervised by Renouvin.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Since Becker doubted the consensus, he set out to find sources that would show the state of public opinion in 1914, and found Petit-Dutaillis's compilation in the library and archive center *La contemporaine*.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Using schoolteachers' reports, cross-referenced with other sources (press, prefectoral records, etc.), he challenged the myth of "*la fleur au fusil.*" He remained convinced, however, that the French massively embraced the war as a national cause.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] While Jean-Jacques Becker's thesis is undisputed for the start of the war, other historians such as Jules Maurin and Philippe Boulanger note that, after the first three months, voluntary enlistments abandoned their patriotic character in favor of a survival strategy.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Indeed, being called up early enabled volunteers to choose their branch of assignment.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Volunteers were more likely to choose the artillery or navy, reputed to be less deadly than the infantry.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] This observation therefore undermines the idea that the French always consented to war.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] These intellectuals regretted that their comrades-in-arms from the common people (peasants, craftsmen or workers) did not share their ideals, many of them patriotic.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] Feeling socially isolated despite an overcrowding that disturbed them, they had little patience for popular swearing or drinking parties.
[src:world-war-i/1914-french-mobilization-p02] The common soldier looked on them with more suspicion than to the officer, who is often a man designated by rank.
[src:world-war-i/1914-ottoman-jihad-proclamation] On 11 November 1914, Ottoman Caliph Mehmed V proclaimed holy war against the Entente powers and appealed for support from Muslims in Entente-controlled countries.
[src:world-war-i/1914-ottoman-jihad-proclamation] The declaration, which called for Muslims to support the Ottomans in Entente-controlled areas and for *jihad* against "all enemies of the Ottoman Empire, except the Central Powers", was initially presented on 11 November and published in *Takvim-i Vekayi* the following day.
[src:world-war-i/1914-ottoman-jihad-proclamation] The proclamation included five *fatwa* or legal opinions endorsed by 29 religious authorities.
[src:world-war-i/1914-ottoman-jihad-proclamation] Several days later, on 14 November, it was read out to a large crowd outside the Fatih Mosque by Ali Haydar Efendi, the *fetva emini* ('custodian of the *fatwa*', the Ottoman official in charge of dictating *tafsir* on behalf of the Shaykh al-Islām).
[src:world-war-i/1914-ottoman-jihad-proclamation] The declaration was seen as mostly ineffective in the war, with the Emirate of Afghanistan avoiding confrontation with the Entente despite pressure from the German and Ottoman Empires and a British-backed revolt taking place against the Ottomans in the Hejaz.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The causes of World War I included the rise of the German Empire and decline of the Ottoman Empire, which disturbed the long-standing balance of power in Europe, the exacerbation of imperial rivalries, and an arms race between the great powers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Growing tensions in the Balkans reached a breaking point on 28 June 1914 when Gavrilo Princip, a Bosnian Serb, assassinated Franz Ferdinand, the heir to the Austro-Hungarian throne.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Austria-Hungary blamed Serbia, and declared war on 28 July.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] After Russia mobilised in Serbia's defence, Germany declared war on Russia and France, who had an alliance.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The United Kingdom entered the war after Germany invaded Belgium, and the Ottoman Empire joined the Central Powers in November.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Germany's strategy in 1914 was to quickly defeat France before transferring its forces to the east, but its advance was halted in September, and by the end of the year the Western Front consisted of a near-continuous line of trenches from the English Channel to Switzerland.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The Eastern Front was more dynamic, but neither side gained a decisive advantage, despite costly offensives.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Italy, Bulgaria, Romania, Greece, and others entered the war from 1915 onward.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Major battles, including those at Verdun, the Somme, and Passchendaele, failed to break the stalemate on the Western Front.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] In April 1917, the United States joined the Allies after Germany resumed unrestricted submarine warfare against Atlantic shipping.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Later that year, the Bolsheviks seized power in Russia in the October Revolution; Soviet Russia signed an armistice with the Central Powers in December, followed by a separate peace in March 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] That month, Germany launched a spring offensive in the west, which despite initial successes left the German Army exhausted and demoralised.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The Allied Hundred Days Offensive, beginning in August 1918, caused a collapse of the German front line.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Following the Vardar Offensive, Bulgaria signed an armistice in late September.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] By early November, the Allies had signed armistices with the Ottomans and with Austria-Hungary, leaving Germany isolated.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Facing a revolution at home, Kaiser Wilhelm II abdicated on 9 November, and the war ended with the Armistice of 11 November 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The Paris Peace Conference of 1919–1920 imposed settlements on the defeated powers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Under the Treaty of Versailles, Germany lost significant territories, was disarmed, and was required to pay large war reparations to the Allies.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The dissolution of the Russian, German, Austro-Hungarian, and Ottoman empires led to new national boundaries and the creation of new independent states including Poland, Finland, the Baltic states, Czechoslovakia, and Yugoslavia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The League of Nations was established to maintain world peace, but its failure to manage instability during the interwar period contributed to the outbreak of World War II in 1939.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Before World War II, the events of 1914–1918 were commonly referred to as the ***Great War*** or simply the ***World War***.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] In August 1914, *The Independent* stated of the conflict, "This is the Great War.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] It names itself." In the decade after its end, many hoped it would be "the war to end all wars," because of its unprecedented destructiveness and death toll.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] For much of the 19th century, the major European powers maintained a tenuous balance of power, known as the Concert of Europe.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] After 1848, this was challenged by Britain's withdrawal into splendid isolation, the decline of the Ottoman Empire, New Imperialism, and the rise of Prussia under Otto von Bismarck.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Victory in the 1870–1871 Franco-Prussian War allowed Bismarck to consolidate a German Empire.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] After 1871, French policy aimed to avenge this defeat and expand France's colonial empire.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] In 1873, Bismarck negotiated the League of the Three Emperors, which included Austria-Hungary, Russia, and Germany.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] After the 1877–1878 Russo-Turkish War, the League was dissolved due to Austrian concerns over the expansion of Russian influence in the Balkans, an area they considered to be of vital strategic interest.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Germany and Austria-Hungary then formed the 1879 Dual Alliance, which became the Triple Alliance when Italy joined in 1882.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] For Bismarck, the purpose of these agreements was to isolate France by ensuring the three empires resolved any disputes among themselves.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] In 1887, Bismarck set up the Reinsurance Treaty, a secret agreement between Germany and Russia to remain neutral if either were attacked by France or Austria-Hungary.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] For Bismarck, peace with Russia was the foundation of German foreign policy, but in 1890, he was forced to retire by Wilhelm II.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The latter was persuaded not to renew the Reinsurance Treaty by his new Chancellor, Leo von Caprivi.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] This gave France an opening to agree to the Franco-Russian Alliance in 1894, which was then followed by the 1904 *Entente Cordiale* with Britain.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The Triple Entente was completed by the 1907 Anglo-Russian Convention.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] While not formal alliances, by settling longstanding colonial disputes in Asia and Africa, British support for France or Russia in any future conflict became a possibility.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] This was accentuated by British and Russian support for France against Germany during the 1911 Agadir Crisis.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] German economic and industrial strength continued to expand rapidly post-1871.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Backed by Wilhelm II, Admiral Alfred von Tirpitz sought to use this growth to build an Imperial German Navy that could compete with the British Royal Navy.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] This policy was based on the work of US naval author Alfred Thayer Mahan, who argued that possession of a blue-water navy was vital for global power projection; Tirpitz had his books translated into German, while Wilhelm made them required reading for his advisors and senior military personnel.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Bismarck opposed any attempt to compete with the Royal Navy, since he believed Britain would not interfere in Europe as long as its maritime supremacy remained secure.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] His dismissal in 1890 led to a change in policy and the start of an Anglo-German naval arms race.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Despite the vast sums spent by Tirpitz, the launch of HMS *Dreadnought* in 1906 made every existing battleship obsolete, and gave the British a technological advantage they never relinquished.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Ultimately, Germany invested huge resources on creating a navy large enough to antagonise Britain, but not defeat it.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] In 1911, Chancellor Theobald von Bethmann Hollweg acknowledged defeat, leading to the *Rüstungswende* or 'armaments turning point', when he switched expenditure from the navy to the army.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] This decision was driven by German concerns over the speed of Russia's recovery from defeat in the Russo-Japanese War and the subsequent 1905 Russian Revolution.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Economic reforms led to a significant post-1908 expansion of railways and transportation infrastructure, particularly in its western border regions.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Since Germany and Austria-Hungary relied on faster mobilisation to compensate for their numerical inferiority compared to Russia, the threat posed by the closing of this gap was more important than competing with the Royal Navy.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] After Germany expanded its standing army by 170,000 troops in 1913, France extended compulsory military service from two to three years, sparking similar measures from the Balkan powers, Italy, the Ottoman Empire and Austria-Hungary.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Absolute figures are difficult to calculate due to differences in categorising expenditure since they often omit civilian infrastructure projects like railways which had logistical importance and military use.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] However, from 1908 to 1913, military spending by the six major European powers increased by over 50% in real terms.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The years before 1914 were marked by a series of crises in the Balkans, as other powers sought to benefit from the Ottoman decline.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] While Pan-Slavic and Orthodox Russia considered itself the protector of Serbia and other Slav states, they preferred the strategically vital Bosporus straits to be controlled by a weak Ottoman government, rather than an ambitious Slav power like Bulgaria.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Russia had ambitions in northeastern Anatolia while its clients had overlapping claims in the Balkans.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] These competing interests divided Russian policy-makers and added to regional instability.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Austrian statesmen viewed the Balkans as essential for the continued existence of their Empire and saw Serbian expansion as a direct threat.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The 1908–1909 Bosnian Crisis began when Austria annexed the former Ottoman territory of Bosnia and Herzegovina, which it had occupied since 1878.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Timed to coincide with the Bulgarian Declaration of Independence from the Ottoman Empire, this unilateral action was denounced by the European powers, but accepted as there was no consensus on how to resolve the situation.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Some historians see this as a significant escalation, ending any chance of Austria cooperating with Russia in the Balkans, while also damaging diplomatic relations between Serbia and Italy.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Tensions increased after the 1911–1912 Italo-Turkish War demonstrated Ottoman weakness and led to the formation of the Balkan League, an alliance of Serbia, Bulgaria, Montenegro, and Greece.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The League quickly overran most of the Ottomans' territory in the Balkans during the 1912–1913 First Balkan War, much to the surprise of outside observers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The Serbian capture of ports on the Adriatic resulted in partial Austrian mobilisation, starting on 21 November 1912, including units along the Russian border in Galicia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The Russian government decided not to mobilise in response, unprepared to precipitate a war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The great powers sought to re-assert control through the 1913 Treaty of London, which had created an independent Albania while enlarging the territories of Bulgaria, Serbia, Montenegro and Greece.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] However, disputes between the victors sparked the 33-day Second Balkan War, when Bulgaria attacked Serbia and Greece on 16 June 1913; it was defeated, losing most of Macedonia to Serbia and Greece, and Southern Dobruja to Romania.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The result was that even countries which benefited from the Balkan Wars, such as Serbia and Greece, felt cheated of their "rightful gains", while for Austria it demonstrated the apparent indifference with which other powers viewed their concerns, including Germany.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] This complex mix of resentment, nationalism and insecurity helps explain why the pre-1914 Balkans became known as the "powder keg of Europe".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] On 28 June 1914, Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria, heir presumptive to Emperor Franz Joseph I of Austria, visited Sarajevo, the capital of the recently annexed Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Cvjetko Popović, Gavrilo Princip, Nedeljko Čabrinović, Trifko Grabež, Vaso Čubrilović (Bosnian Serbs) and Muhamed Mehmedbašić (from the Bosniaks community), from the movement known as Young Bosnia, took up positions along the Archduke's motorcade route, to assassinate him.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Supplied with arms by extremists within the Serbian Black Hand intelligence organisation, they hoped his death would free Bosnia from Austrian rule.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Čabrinović threw a grenade at the Archduke's car and injured two of his aides.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The other assassins were also unsuccessful.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] An hour later, as Ferdinand was returning from visiting the injured officers in hospital, his car took a wrong turn into a street where Gavrilo Princip was standing.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] He fired two pistol shots, fatally wounding Ferdinand and his wife Sophie.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] According to historian Zbyněk Zeman, in Vienna "the event almost failed to make any impression whatsoever.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Austro-Hungarian authorities encouraged subsequent anti-Serb riots in Sarajevo.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Violent actions against ethnic Serbs were also organised outside Sarajevo, in other cities in Austro-Hungarian-controlled Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and Slovenia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Austro-Hungarian authorities in Bosnia and Herzegovina imprisoned approximately 5,500 prominent Serbs, 700 to 2,200 of whom died in prison.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] A further 460 Serbs were sentenced to death.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] A predominantly Bosniak special militia known as the *Schutzkorps* was established, and carried out the persecution of Serbs.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The assassination initiated the July Crisis, a month of diplomatic manoeuvring among Austria-Hungary, Germany, Russia, France and Britain.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Believing that Serbian intelligence helped organise Franz Ferdinand's murder, Austrian officials wanted to use the opportunity to end Serbian interference in Bosnia and saw war as the best way of achieving this.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] However, the Foreign Ministry had no solid proof of Serbian involvement.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] On 23 July, Austria delivered an ultimatum to Serbia, listing ten demands made intentionally unacceptable to provide an excuse for starting hostilities.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Serbia ordered general mobilisation on 25 July, but accepted all the terms, except for those empowering Austrian representatives to suppress "subversive elements" inside Serbia, and take part in the investigation and trial of Serbians linked to the assassination.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Claiming this amounted to rejection, Austria broke off diplomatic relations and ordered partial mobilisation the next day; on 28 July, they declared war on Serbia and began shelling Belgrade.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Russia ordered general mobilisation in support of Serbia on 30 July.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Anxious to ensure backing from the SPD political opposition by presenting Russia as the aggressor, German Chancellor Bethmann Hollweg delayed the commencement of war preparations until 31 July.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] That afternoon, the Russian government were handed a note requiring them to "cease all war measures against Germany and Austria-Hungary" within 12 hours.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] A further German demand for neutrality was refused by the French who ordered general mobilisation but delayed declaring war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] The German General Staff had long assumed they faced a war on two fronts; the Schlieffen Plan envisaged using 80% of the army to defeat France, then switching to Russia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Since this required them to move quickly, mobilisation orders were issued that afternoon.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Once the German ultimatum to Russia expired on the morning of 1 August, the two countries were at war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] On 31 July, Britain sent notes to Germany and France, asking them to respect Belgian neutrality; France pledged to do so, but Germany did not reply.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Aware of German plans to attack through Belgium, French Commander-in-Chief Joseph Joffre asked his government for permission to cross the border and pre-empt such a move.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] To avoid violating Belgian neutrality, he was told any advance could come only after a German invasion.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Instead, the French cabinet ordered its Army to withdraw 10 km behind the German frontier, to avoid provoking war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] On 2 August, Germany occupied Luxembourg and exchanged fire with French units when German patrols entered French territory; on 3 August, they declared war on France and demanded free passage across Belgium, which was refused.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Early on the morning of 4 August, the Germans invaded, and Albert I of Belgium called for assistance under the Treaty of London.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p01] Britain sent Germany an ultimatum demanding they withdraw from Belgium; when this expired at midnight, without a response, the two empires were at war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Germany promised to support Austria-Hungary's invasion of Serbia, but interpretations of what this meant differed.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Previously tested deployment plans had been replaced early in 1914, but those had never been tested in exercises.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Austro-Hungarian leaders believed Germany would cover its northern flank against Russia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Beginning on 12 August, the Austrians and Serbs clashed at the battles of the Cer and Kolubara; over the next two weeks, Austrian attacks were repulsed with heavy losses.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] As a result, Austria had to keep sizeable forces on the Serbian front, weakening their efforts against Russia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Serbia's victory against Austria-Hungary in the 1914 invasion has been called one of the major upset victories of the twentieth century.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In 1915, the campaign saw the first use of anti-aircraft warfare after an Austrian plane was shot down with ground-to-air fire, as well as the first medical evacuation by the Serbian army.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Upon mobilisation, in accordance with the Schlieffen Plan, 80% of the German Army was located on the Western Front, with the remainder acting as a screening force in the East.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Rather than a direct attack across their shared frontier, the German right wing would sweep through the Netherlands and Belgium, then swing south, encircling Paris and trapping the French army against the Swiss border.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The plan's creator, Alfred von Schlieffen, head of the German General Staff from 1891 to 1906, estimated that this would take six weeks, after which the German army would transfer to the East and defeat the Russians.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The plan was substantially modified by his successor, Helmuth von Moltke the Younger.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Under Schlieffen, 85% of German forces in the west were assigned to the right wing, with the remainder holding along the frontier.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] By keeping his left-wing deliberately weak, he hoped to lure the French into an offensive into the "lost provinces" of Alsace-Lorraine, which was the strategy envisaged by their Plan XVII.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, Moltke grew concerned that the French might push too hard on his left flank and as the German Army increased in size from 1908 to 1914, he changed the allocation of forces between the two wings to 70:30.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] He also considered Dutch neutrality essential for German trade and cancelled the incursion into the Netherlands, which meant any delays in Belgium threatened the viability of the plan.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Historian Richard Holmes argues that these changes meant the right wing was not strong enough to achieve decisive success.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The initial German advance in the West was very successful.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] By the end of August, the Allied left, which included the British Expeditionary Force (BEF), was in full retreat, and the French offensive in Alsace-Lorraine was a disastrous failure, with casualties exceeding 260,000.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] German planning provided broad strategic instructions while allowing army commanders considerable freedom in carrying them out at the front, but Alexander von Kluck used this freedom to disobey orders, opening a gap between the German armies as they closed on Paris.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The French army, reinforced by the British expeditionary corps, seized this opportunity to counter-attack and pushed the German army 40 to 80 km back.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Both armies were then so exhausted that no decisive move could be implemented, so they settled in trenches, with the vain hope of breaking through as soon as they could build local superiority.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In 1911, the Russian Stavka agreed with the French to attack Germany within fifteen days of mobilisation, ten days before the Germans had anticipated, although it meant the two Russian armies that entered East Prussia on 17 August did so without many of their support elements.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] By the end of 1914, German troops held strong defensive positions inside France, controlled the bulk of France's domestic coalfields, and inflicted 230,000 more casualties than it lost itself.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, communications problems and questionable command decisions cost Germany the chance of a decisive outcome, while it had failed to achieve the primary objective of avoiding a long, two-front war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] As was apparent to several German leaders, this amounted to a strategic defeat; shortly after the First Battle of the Marne, Crown Prince Wilhelm told an American reporter "We have lost the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 30 August 1914, New Zealand occupied German Samoa (now Samoa).
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 11 September, the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed on the island of New Britain, then part of German New Guinea.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 28 October, the German cruiser SMS *Emden* sank the Russian cruiser *Zhemchug* in the Battle of Penang.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Japan declared war on Germany before seizing territories in the Pacific, which later became the South Seas Mandate, as well as German Treaty ports on the Chinese Shandong peninsula at Tsingtao.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] After Vienna refused to withdraw its cruiser SMS *Kaiserin Elisabeth* from Tsingtao, Japan declared war on Austria-Hungary, and the ship was scuttled in November 1914.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Within a few months, Allied forces had seized all German territories in the Pacific, leaving only isolated commerce raiders and a few holdouts in New Guinea.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Some of the first clashes of the war involved British, French, and German colonial forces in Africa.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 6–7 August, French and British troops invaded the German protectorates of Togoland and Kamerun.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 10 August, German forces in South-West Africa attacked South Africa; sporadic and fierce fighting continued for the rest of the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The German colonial forces in German East Africa, led by Colonel Paul von Lettow-Vorbeck, fought a guerrilla warfare campaign and only surrendered two weeks after the armistice took effect in Europe.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Before the war, Germany had attempted to use Indian nationalism and pan-Islamism to its advantage, a policy continued post-1914 by instigating uprisings in India, while the Niedermayer–Hentig Expedition urged Afghanistan to join the war on the side of Central Powers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, contrary to British fears of a revolt in India, the outbreak of the war saw a reduction in nationalist activity.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Leaders from the Indian National Congress and other groups believed support for the British war effort would hasten Indian Home Rule, a promise allegedly made explicit in 1917 by Edwin Montagu, the Secretary of State for India.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In 1914, the British Indian Army was larger than the British Army itself, and between 1914 and 1918 an estimated 1.3 million Indian soldiers and labourers served in Europe, Africa, and the Middle East.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In all, 140,000 soldiers served on the Western Front and nearly 700,000 in the Middle East, with 47,746 killed and 65,126 wounded.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The suffering engendered by the war, as well as the failure of the British government to grant self-government to India afterward, bred disillusionment, resulting in the campaign for full independence led by Mahatma Gandhi.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Pre-war military tactics that had emphasised open warfare and individual riflemen proved obsolete when confronted with conditions prevailing in 1914.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Barbed wire, machine guns and artillery allowed the creation of strong defensive systems that made massed infantry advances extremely difficult.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Both sides struggled to develop tactics for breaching entrenched positions without heavy casualties.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In time, the tank helped to make the front more mobile.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] After the First Battle of the Marne in September 1914, Allied and German forces unsuccessfully tried to outflank each other, a series of manoeuvres later known as the "Race to the Sea".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] By the end of 1914, the opposing forces confronted each other along an uninterrupted line of entrenched positions from the Channel to the Swiss border.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Since the Germans were normally able to choose where to stand, they generally held the high ground, while their trenches tended to be better built; those constructed by the French and English were initially considered "temporary", only needed until an offensive would destroy the German defences.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Both sides tried to break the stalemate using scientific and technological advances.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 22 April 1915, at the Second Battle of Ypres, the Germans (violating the Hague Convention) used chlorine gas for the first time on the Western Front.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In February 1916, the Germans attacked French defensive positions at the Battle of Verdun, lasting until December 1916.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Casualties were greater for the French, but the Germans bled heavily as well, with anywhere from 700,000 to 975,000 casualties between the two combatants.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Verdun became a symbol of French determination and self-sacrifice.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Battle of the Somme was an Anglo-French offensive from July to November 1916.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The opening day, on 1 July 1916, was the bloodiest single day in the history of the British Army, which suffered 57,500 casualties, including 19,200 dead.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] As a whole, the Somme offensive led to an estimated 420,000 British casualties, along with 200,000 French and 500,000 Germans.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The diseases that emerged in the trenches were a major killer on both sides.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The living conditions led to disease and infection, such as trench foot, lice, typhus, trench fever, and the 'Spanish flu'.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] At the start of the war, German cruisers were scattered across the globe, some of which were subsequently used to attack Allied merchant shipping.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] These were systematically hunted down by the Royal Navy, though not before causing considerable damage.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] One of the most successful was the SMS *Emden*, part of the German East Asia Squadron stationed at Qingdao, which seized or sank 15 merchantmen, a Russian cruiser and a French destroyer.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Most of the squadron was returning to Germany when it sank two British armoured cruisers at the Battle of Coronel in November 1914, before being virtually destroyed at the Battle of the Falkland Islands in December.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The SMS *Dresden* escaped with a few auxiliaries, but after the Battle of Más a Tierra, these too were either destroyed or interned.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Soon after the outbreak of hostilities, Britain began a naval blockade of Germany.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] This proved effective in cutting off vital supplies, though it violated accepted international law.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Britain also mined international waters which closed off entire sections of the ocean, even to neutral ships.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Since there was limited response to this tactic, Germany expected a similar response to its unrestricted submarine warfare.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Battle of Jutland in May/June 1916 was the only full-scale clash of battleships during the war, and one of the largest in history.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The clash was indecisive, though the Germans inflicted more damage than they received; thereafter the bulk of the German High Seas Fleet was confined to port.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] German U-boats attempted to cut the supply lines between North America and Britain.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The nature of submarine warfare meant that attacks often came without warning, giving the crews of the merchant ships little hope of survival.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The United States launched a protest, and Germany changed its rules of engagement.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Finally, in early 1917, Germany adopted a policy of unrestricted submarine warfare, realising the Americans would eventually enter the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Germany sought to strangle Allied sea lanes before the United States could transport a large army overseas, but, after initial successes, eventually failed to do so.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The U-boat threat lessened in 1917, when merchant ships began travelling in convoys, escorted by destroyers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] This tactic made it difficult for U-boats to find targets, which significantly lessened losses; after the hydrophone and depth charges were introduced, destroyers could potentially successfully attack a submerged submarine.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Convoys slowed the flow of supplies since ships had to wait as convoys were assembled; the solution was an extensive program of building new freighters.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Troopships were too fast for the submarines and did not travel the North Atlantic in convoys.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The U-boats sunk more than 5,000 Allied ships, at the cost of 199 submarines.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] World War I also saw the first use of aircraft carriers in combat, with HMS *Furious* launching Sopwith Camels in a successful raid against the Zeppelin hangars at Tondern in July 1918, as well as blimps for antisubmarine patrol.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Faced with Russia in the east, Austria-Hungary could spare only one-third of its army to attack Serbia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] After suffering heavy losses, the Austrians briefly occupied the Serbian capital, Belgrade.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] A Serbian counter-attack in the Battle of Kolubara succeeded in driving them from the country by the end of 1914.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] For the first 10 months of 1915, Austria-Hungary used most of its military reserves to fight Italy.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] German and Austro-Hungarian diplomats scored a coup by persuading Bulgaria to join the attack on Serbia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Austro-Hungarian provinces of Slovenia, Croatia and Bosnia provided troops for Austria-Hungary.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Bulgaria declared war on Serbia on 14 October 1915, and joined in the attack by the Austro-Hungarian army under Mackensen's army of 250,000 that was already underway.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Serbia was conquered in a little more than a month, as the Central Powers, now including Bulgaria, sent in 600,000 troops in total.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Serbian army, fighting on two fronts and facing certain defeat, retreated into northern Albania.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Serbs suffered defeat in the Battle of Kosovo.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Montenegro covered the Serbian retreat toward the Adriatic coast in the Battle of Mojkovac on 6–7 January 1916, but ultimately the Austrians also conquered Montenegro.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The surviving Serbian soldiers were evacuated to Greece.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] After the conquest, Serbia was divided between Austro-Hungary and Bulgaria.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In late 1915, a Franco-British force landed at Salonica in Greece to offer assistance and to pressure its government to declare war against the Central Powers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, the pro-German King Constantine I dismissed the pro-Allied government of Eleftherios Venizelos before the Allied expeditionary force arrived.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Macedonian front was at first mostly static.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] French and Serbian forces retook limited areas of Macedonia by recapturing Bitola on 19 November 1916, following the costly Monastir offensive, which brought stabilisation of the front.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Serbian and French troops finally made a breakthrough in September 1918 in the Vardar offensive, after most German and Austro-Hungarian troops had been withdrawn.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Bulgarians were defeated at the Battle of Dobro Pole, and by 25 September British and French troops had crossed the border into Bulgaria proper as the Bulgarian army collapsed.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Bulgaria capitulated four days later, on 29 September 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The German high command responded by despatching troops to hold the line, but these forces were too weak to re-establish a front.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Allied breakthrough on the Macedonian front cut communications between the Ottoman Empire and the other Central Powers, and made Vienna vulnerable to attack.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Hindenburg and Ludendorff concluded that the strategic and operational balance had now shifted decidedly against the Central Powers and, a day after the Bulgarian collapse, insisted on an immediate peace settlement.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Ottomans threatened Russia's Caucasian territories and Britain's communications with India via the Suez Canal.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Ottoman Empire took advantage of the European powers' preoccupation with the war and conducted large-scale ethnic cleansing of the Armenian, Greek, and Assyrian Christian populations—the Armenian genocide, Greek genocide, and Assyrian genocide respectively.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The British and French opened overseas fronts with the Gallipoli (1915) and Mesopotamian campaigns (1914).
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In Gallipoli, the Ottoman Empire successfully repelled the British, French, and Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZACs).
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In Mesopotamia, by contrast, after the defeat of the British defenders in the siege of Kut by the Ottomans (1915–1916), British Imperial forces reorganised and captured Baghdad in March 1917.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The British were aided in Mesopotamia by local Arab and Assyrian fighters, while the Ottomans employed local Kurdish and Turcoman tribes.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Suez Canal was defended from Ottoman attacks in 1915 and 1916; in August 1916, a German and Ottoman force was defeated at the Battle of Romani by the ANZAC Mounted Division and the 52nd (Lowland) Infantry Division.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Following this victory, an Egyptian Expeditionary Force advanced across the Sinai Peninsula, pushing Ottoman forces back in the Battle of Magdhaba in December and the Battle of Rafa on the border between the Egyptian Sinai and Ottoman Palestine in January 1917.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Russian armies generally had success in the Caucasus campaign.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Enver Pasha, supreme commander of the Ottoman armed forces, dreamed of re-conquering central Asia and areas that had been previously lost to Russia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] He launched an offensive against the Russians in the Caucasus in December 1914 with 100,000 troops, insisting on a frontal attack against mountainous Russian positions in winter.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] He lost 86% of his force at the Battle of Sarikamish.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] General Nikolai Yudenich, the Russian commander from 1915 to 1916, drove the Turks out of most of the southern Caucasus.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Ottoman Empire, with German support, invaded Persia (modern Iran) in December 1914 to cut off British and Russian access to petroleum reservoirs around Baku.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Persia, ostensibly neutral, had long been under British and Russian influence.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Ottomans and Germans were aided by Kurdish and Azeri forces, together with a large number of major Iranian tribes, while the Russians and British had the support of Armenian and Assyrian forces.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Persian campaign lasted until 1918 and ended in failure for the Ottomans and their allies.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, the Russian withdrawal from the war in 1917 led Armenian and Assyrian forces to be cut off from supply lines, outnumbered, outgunned and isolated, forcing them to fight and flee towards British lines in northern Mesopotamia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Arab Revolt, instigated by the British Foreign Office, started in June 1916 with the Battle of Mecca, led by Sharif Hussein.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Sharif declared the independence of the Kingdom of Hejaz and, with British assistance, conquered much of Ottoman-held Arabia, resulting finally in the Ottoman surrender of Damascus.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Fakhri Pasha, the Ottoman commander of Medina, resisted for more than 2+1⁄2 years during the siege of Medina before surrendering in January 1919.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Senussi tribe, along the border of Italian Libya and British Egypt, incited and armed by the Turks, waged a small-scale guerrilla war against Allied troops.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The British were forced to dispatch 12,000 troops to oppose them in the Senussi campaign.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Their rebellion was finally crushed in mid-1916.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Total Allied casualties on the Ottoman fronts amounted to 650,000 men.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Though Italy joined the Triple Alliance in 1882, a treaty with its traditional Austrian enemy was so controversial that subsequent governments denied its existence and the terms were only made public in 1915.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] This arose from nationalist designs on Austro-Hungarian territory in Trentino, the Austrian Littoral, Rijeka and Dalmatia, considered vital to secure the borders established in 1866.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In 1902, Rome secretly had agreed with France to remain neutral if the latter was attacked by Germany, effectively nullifying its role in the Triple Alliance.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] When the war began in 1914, Italy argued the Triple Alliance was defensive and it was not obliged to support an Austrian attack on Serbia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Opposition to joining the Central Powers increased when Turkey became a member in September, since in 1911 Italy had occupied Ottoman possessions in Libya and the Dodecanese islands.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] To secure Italian neutrality, the Central Powers offered them Tunisia, while in return for an immediate entry into the war, the Allies agreed to their demands for Austrian territory and sovereignty over the Dodecanese.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Although they remained secret, these provisions were incorporated into the April 1915 Treaty of London, and Italy joined the Allies.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 23 May, Italy declared war on Austria-Hungary, and on Germany fifteen months later.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The pre-1914 Italian army was short of officers, trained men, adequate transport and modern weapons; by April 1915, some of these deficiencies had been remedied but it was still unprepared for the major offensive required by the Treaty of London.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The advantage of superior numbers was offset by the difficult terrain; much of the fighting took place high in the Alps and Dolomites, where trench lines had to be cut through rock and ice and keeping troops supplied was a major challenge.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] These issues were exacerbated by unimaginative strategies and tactics.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Between 1915 and 1917, the Italian commander, Luigi Cadorna, undertook a series of frontal assaults along the Isonzo, which made little progress and cost many lives; by the end of the war, Italian combat deaths totalled around 548,000.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In the spring of 1916, the Austro-Hungarians counterattacked in Asiago in the *Strafexpedition*, but made little progress and were pushed by the Italians back to Tyrol.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Although Italy occupied southern Albania in May 1916, their main focus was the Isonzo front which, after the capture of Gorizia in August 1916, remained static until October 1917.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] After a combined Austro-German force won a major victory at Caporetto, Cadorna was replaced by Armando Diaz who retreated more than 100 kilometres (62 mi) before holding positions along the Piave River.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] A second Austrian offensive was repulsed in June 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 24 October, Diaz launched the Battle of Vittorio Veneto and initially met stubborn resistance, but with Austria-Hungary collapsing, Hungarian divisions in Italy demanded they be sent home.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] When this was granted, many others followed and the Imperial army disintegrated, the Italians taking over 300,000 prisoners.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 3 November, the Armistice of Villa Giusti ended hostilities between Austria-Hungary and Italy which occupied Trieste and areas along the Adriatic Sea awarded to it in 1915.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] As previously agreed with French president Raymond Poincaré, Russian plans at the start of the war were to simultaneously advance into Austrian Galicia and East Prussia as soon as possible.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Although their attack on Galicia was largely successful, and the invasions achieved their aim of forcing Germany to divert troops from the Western Front, the speed of mobilisation meant they did so without much of their heavy equipment and support functions.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] These weaknesses contributed to Russian defeats at Tannenberg and the Masurian Lakes in August and September 1914, forcing them to withdraw from East Prussia with heavy losses.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] By spring 1915, they had also retreated from Galicia, and the May 1915 Gorlice–Tarnów offensive allowed the Central Powers to invade Russian-occupied Poland.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Despite the successful June 1916 Brusilov offensive against the Austrians in eastern Galicia, shortages of supplies, heavy losses and command failures prevented the Russians from fully exploiting their victory.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, it was one of the most significant offensives of the war, diverting German resources from Verdun, relieving Austro-Hungarian pressure on the Italians, and convincing Romania to enter the war on the side of the Allies on 27 August.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] It also fatally weakened both the Austrian and Russian armies, whose offensive capabilities were badly affected by their losses and increased disillusion with the war that ultimately led to the Russian revolutions.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Meanwhile, unrest grew in Russia as Tsar Nicholas II remained at the front, with the home front controlled by Empress Alexandra.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Her increasingly incompetent rule and food shortages in urban areas led to widespread protests and the murder of her favourite, Grigori Rasputin, at the end of 1916.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] With the ruling elite split into pro-German and pro-Entente factions, Romania remained neutral for two years while allowing Germany and Austria to transport military supplies and advisors across Romanian territory.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In September 1914, Russia acknowledged Romanian rights to Austro-Hungarian territories including Transylvania and Banat, whose acquisition had widespread popular support, and Russian success against Austria led Romania to join the Entente in the August 1916 Treaty of Bucharest.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Under the strategic plan known as Hypothesis Z, the Romanian army planned an offensive into Transylvania, while defending Southern Dobruja and Giurgiu against a possible Bulgarian counterattack.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 27 August 1916, they attacked Transylvania and occupied substantial parts of the province before being driven back by the recently formed German 9th Army, led by former Chief of Staff Erich von Falkenhayn.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] A combined German-Bulgarian-Turkish offensive captured Dobruja and Giurgiu, although the bulk of the Romanian army managed to escape encirclement and retreated to Bucharest, which surrendered to the Central Powers on 6 December 1916.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In the summer of 1917, a Central Powers offensive began in Romania under the command of August von Mackensen to knock Romania out of the war, resulting in the battles of Oituz, Mărăști and Mărășești, where up to 1,000,000 Central Powers troops were present.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The battles lasted from 22 July to 3 September and eventually the Romanian army was victorious advancing 500 km2.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] August von Mackensen could not plan for another offensive as he had to transfer troops to the Italian Front.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Although approved by Parliament, King Ferdinand I refused to sign it, hoping for an Allied victory in the west.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Romania re-entered the war on 10 November 1918, on the side of the Allies and the Treaty of Bucharest was formally annulled by the Armistice of 11 November 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 12 December 1916, after ten brutal months of the Battle of Verdun and a successful offensive against Romania, Germany attempted to negotiate a peace with the Allies.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, this attempt was rejected out of hand as a "duplicitous war ruse".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] US president Woodrow Wilson attempted to intervene as a peacemaker, asking for both sides to state their demands.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Lloyd George's War Cabinet considered the German offer to be a ploy to create divisions among the Allies.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] After initial outrage and much deliberation, they took Wilson's note as a separate effort, signalling that the US was on the verge of entering the war against Germany following the "submarine outrages".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] While the Allies debated a response to Wilson's offer, the Germans chose to rebuff it in favour of "a direct exchange of views".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Learning of the German response, the Allied governments were free to make clear demands in their response of 14 January.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] They sought restoration of damages, the evacuation of occupied territories, reparations for France, Russia and Romania, and a recognition of the principle of nationalities.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Allies sought guarantees that would prevent or limit future wars.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The negotiations failed and the Entente powers rejected the German offer on the grounds of honour, and noted Germany had not put forward any specific proposals.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] By the end of 1916, Russian casualties totalled nearly five million killed, wounded or captured, with major urban areas affected by food shortages and high prices.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In March 1917, Tsar Nicholas ordered the military to forcibly suppress strikes in Petrograd but the troops refused to fire on the crowds.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Revolutionaries set up the Petrograd Soviet and fearing a left-wing takeover, the State Duma forced Nicholas to abdicate and established the Russian Provisional Government, which confirmed Russia's willingness to continue the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, the Petrograd Soviet refused to disband, creating competing power centres and causing confusion and chaos, with frontline soldiers becoming increasingly demoralised.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Following the tsar's abdication, Vladimir Lenin—with the help of the German government—was ushered from Switzerland into Russia on 16 April 1917.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Discontent and the weaknesses of the Provisional Government led to a rise in the popularity of the Bolshevik Party, led by Lenin, which demanded an immediate end to the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Revolution of November was followed in December by an armistice and negotiations with Germany.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] At first, the Bolsheviks refused the German terms, but when German troops began marching across Ukraine unopposed, they acceded to the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk on 3 March 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The treaty ceded vast territories, including Finland, Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania, and parts of Poland and Ukraine to the Central Powers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] With the Russian Empire out of the war, Romania found itself alone on the Eastern Front and signed the Treaty of Bucharest with the Central Powers in May 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Under the terms of the treaty, Romania ceded territory to Austria-Hungary and Bulgaria and leased its oil reserves to Germany.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] However, the terms also included the Central Powers' recognition of the union of Bessarabia with Romania.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The United States was a major supplier of war materiel to the Allies but remained neutral in 1914, in large part due to domestic opposition.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The most significant factor in creating the support Wilson needed was the German submarine offensive, which not only cost American lives but paralysed trade as ships were reluctant to put to sea.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 6 April 1917, Congress declared war on Germany as an "Associated Power" of the Allies.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The US Navy sent a battleship group to Scapa Flow to join the Grand Fleet, and provided convoy escorts.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In April 1917, the US Army had fewer than 300,000 men, including National Guard units, compared to British and French armies of 4.1 and 8.3 million respectively.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Selective Service Act of 1917 drafted 2.8 million men, though training and equipping such numbers was a huge logistical challenge.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] By June 1918, over 667,000 members of the American Expeditionary Forces (AEF) were transported to France, a figure which reached 2 million by the end of November.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Despite his conviction that Germany must be defeated, Wilson went to war to ensure the US played a leading role in shaping the peace, which meant preserving the AEF as a separate military force, rather than being absorbed into British or French units as his Allies wanted.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] He was strongly supported by AEF commander General John J.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Pershing, a proponent of pre-1914 "open warfare" who considered the French and British emphasis on artillery misguided and incompatible with American "offensive spirit".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Much to the frustration of his Allies, who had suffered heavy losses in 1917, he insisted on retaining control of American troops, and refused to commit them to the front line until able to operate as independent units.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] As a result, the first significant US involvement was the Meuse–Argonne offensive in late September 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In December 1916, Robert Nivelle replaced Pétain as commander of French armies on the Western Front and began planning a spring attack in Champagne, part of a joint Franco-British operation.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Poor security meant German intelligence was well informed on tactics and timetables, but despite this, when the attack began on 16 April the French made substantial gains, before being brought to a halt by the newly built and extremely strong defences of the Hindenburg Line.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Nivelle persisted with frontal assaults and, by 25 April, the French had suffered nearly 135,000 casualties, including 30,000 dead, most incurred in the first two days.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Concurrent British attacks at Arras were more successful, though ultimately of little strategic value.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Operating as a separate unit for the first time, the Canadian Corps' capture of Vimy Ridge is viewed by many Canadians as a defining moment in creating a sense of national identity.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In March and April 1917, at the First and Second Battles of Gaza, German and Ottoman forces stopped the advance of the Egyptian Expeditionary Force, which had begun in August 1916 at the Battle of Romani.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] At the end of October 1917, the Sinai and Palestine campaign resumed, when General Edmund Allenby's XXth Corps, XXI Corps and Desert Mounted Corps won the Battle of Beersheba.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Two Ottoman armies were defeated a few weeks later at the Battle of Mughar Ridge and, early in December, Jerusalem had been captured following another Ottoman defeat at the Battle of Jerusalem.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] About this time, Friedrich Freiherr Kress von Kressenstein was relieved of his duties as the Eighth Army's commander, replaced by Djevad Pasha, and a few months later the commander of the Ottoman Army in Palestine, Erich von Falkenhayn, was replaced by Otto Liman von Sanders.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In early 1918, the front line was extended and the Jordan Valley was occupied, following the First Transjordan and the Second Transjordan attacks by British Empire forces in March and April 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In December 1917, the Central Powers signed an armistice with Russia, thus freeing large numbers of German troops for use in the West.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] With German reinforcements and new American troops pouring in, the outcome was to be decided on the Western Front.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Central Powers knew that they could not win a protracted war, but they held high hopes for success in a final quick offensive.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Ludendorff drew up plans (Operation Michael) for the 1918 offensive on the Western Front.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The operation commenced on 21 March 1918, with an attack on British forces near Saint-Quentin.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] German forces achieved an unprecedented advance of 60 kilometres (37 mi).
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The initial offensive was a success; after heavy fighting, however, the offensive was halted.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Lacking tanks or motorised artillery, the Germans were unable to consolidate their gains.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The problems of re-supply were also exacerbated by increasing distances that now stretched over terrain that was shell-torn and often impassable to traffic.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Germany launched Operation Georgette against the northern English Channel ports.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Allies halted the drive after limited territorial gains by Germany.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The German Army to the south then conducted Operations Blücher and Yorck, pushing broadly towards Paris.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Germany launched Operation Marne (Second Battle of the Marne) on 15 July, in an attempt to encircle Reims.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The resulting counter-attack, which started the Hundred Days Offensive on 8 August, led to a marked collapse in German morale.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] By September, the Germans had fallen back to the Hindenburg Line.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Allies had advanced to the Hindenburg Line in the north and centre.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] German forces launched numerous counterattacks, but positions and outposts of the Line continued falling, with the BEF alone taking 30,441 prisoners in the last week of September.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 24 September, the Supreme Army Command informed the leaders in Berlin that armistice talks were inevitable.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The final assault on the Hindenburg Line began with the Meuse-Argonne offensive, launched by American and French troops on 26 September.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Two days later the Belgians, French and British attacked around Ypres, and the day after the British at St Quentin in the centre of the line.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The following week, cooperating American and French units broke through in Champagne at the Battle of Blanc Mont Ridge (3–27 October), forcing the Germans off the commanding heights, and closing towards the Belgian frontier.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 8 October, the Hindenburg Line was pierced by British and Dominion troops of the First and Third British Armies at the Second Battle of Cambrai.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Allied forces started the Vardar offensive on 15 September at two key points: Dobro Pole and near Dojran Lake.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In the Battle of Dobro Pole, the Serbian and French armies had success after a three-day-long battle with relatively small casualties, and subsequently made a breakthrough in the front, something which was rarely seen in World War I.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] After the front was broken, Allied forces started to liberate Serbia and reached Skopje at 29 September, after which Bulgaria signed an armistice with the Allies on 30 September.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The collapse of the Central Powers came swiftly.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Bulgaria was the first to sign an armistice, the Armistice of Salonica on 29 September 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Wilhelm II, in a telegram to Tsar Ferdinand I of Bulgaria described the situation thus: "Disgraceful!
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On the same day, the German Supreme Army Command informed Wilhelm II and the Imperial Chancellor Count Georg von Hertling, that the military situation facing Germany was hopeless.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 24 October, the Italians began a push that rapidly recovered territory lost after the Battle of Caporetto.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] This culminated in the Battle of Vittorio Veneto, marking the end of the Austro-Hungarian Army as an effective fighting force.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The offensive also triggered the disintegration of the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] During the last week of October, declarations of independence were made in Budapest, Prague, and Zagreb.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 29 October, the imperial authorities asked Italy for an armistice, but the Italians continued advancing, reaching Trento, Udine, and Trieste.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 3 November, Austria-Hungary sent a flag of truce and accepted the Armistice of Villa Giusti, arranged with the Allied Authorities in Paris.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Austria and Hungary signed separate armistices following the overthrow of the Habsburg monarchy.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In the following days, the Italian Army occupied Innsbruck and all Tyrol, with over 20,000 soldiers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] On 30 October, the Ottoman Empire capitulated, and signed the Armistice of Mudros.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] With the military faltering and with widespread loss of confidence in Wilhelm II, Germany moved towards surrender.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Prince Maximilian of Baden took charge on 3 October as Chancellor of Germany.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Negotiations with President Wilson began immediately, in the hope that he would offer better terms than the British and French.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Wilson demanded a constitutional monarchy and parliamentary control over the German military.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The German Revolution of 1918–1919 began at the end of October 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Units of the German Navy refused to set sail for a large-scale operation in a war they believed to be as good as lost.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The sailors' revolt, which then ensued in the naval ports of Wilhelmshaven and Kiel, spread across the whole country within days and led to the proclamation of a republic on 9 November 1918, shortly thereafter to the abdication of Wilhelm II, and German surrender.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In the aftermath of the war, the German, Austro-Hungarian, Ottoman, and Russian empires disappeared.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Numerous nations regained their former independence, and new ones were created.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Four dynasties fell as a result of the war: the Romanovs, the Hohenzollerns, the Habsburgs, and the Ottomans.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Belgium and Serbia were badly damaged, as was France, with 1.4 million soldiers dead, not counting other casualties.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Germany and Russia were similarly affected.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] A formal state of war between the two sides persisted for another seven months, until the signing of the Treaty of Versailles with Germany on 28 June 1919.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The US Senate did not ratify the treaty despite public support for it,and did not formally end its involvement in the war until the Knox–Porter Resolution was signed on 2 July 1921 by President Warren G.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Some war memorials date the end of the war as being when the Versailles Treaty was signed in 1919, which was when many of the troops serving abroad finally returned home; by contrast, most commemorations of the war's end concentrate on the armistice of 11 November 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Paris Peace Conference imposed a series of peace treaties on the Central Powers officially ending the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The 1919 Treaty of Versailles dealt with Germany and, building on Wilson's 14th point, established the League of Nations on 28 June 1919.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Central Powers had to acknowledge responsibility for "all the loss and damage to which the Allied and Associated Governments and their nationals have been subjected as a consequence of the war imposed upon them by" their aggression.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In the Treaty of Versailles, this statement was Article 231.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] This article became known as the "War Guilt Clause", as the majority of Germans felt humiliated and resentful.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Germans felt they had been unjustly dealt with by what they called the "diktat of Versailles".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Meanwhile, new nations liberated from German rule viewed the treaty as a recognition of wrongs committed against small nations by much larger aggressive neighbours.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Austria-Hungary was partitioned into several successor states, largely but not entirely along ethnic lines.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Czechoslovakia, Italy, Poland, Romania and Yugoslavia received territories from the Dual Monarchy (while the formerly separate and autonomous Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia was incorporated into Yugoslavia).
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The details were contained in the treaties of Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Trianon.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] As a result, Hungary lost 64% of its total population, decreasing from 20.9 million to 7.6 million, and losing 31% (3.3 out of 10.7 million) of its ethnic Hungarians.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] According to the 1910 census, speakers of the Hungarian language included approximately 54% of the entire population of the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Within the country, numerous ethnic minorities were present: 16.1% Romanians, 10.5% Slovaks, 10.4% Germans, 2.5% Ruthenians, 2.5% Serbs, and 8% others.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Between 1920 and 1924, 354,000 Hungarians fled former Hungarian territories attached to Romania, Czechoslovakia, and Yugoslavia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Russian Empire lost much of its western frontier as the newly independent nations of Estonia, Finland, Latvia, Lithuania, and Poland were carved from it.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Romania took control of Bessarabia in April 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] After 123 years, Poland re-emerged as an independent country.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] The Kingdom of Serbia and its dynasty, as a "minor Entente nation" and the country with the most casualties per capita, became the backbone of a new multinational state, the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes, later renamed Yugoslavia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Czechoslovakia, combining the Kingdom of Bohemia with parts of the Kingdom of Hungary, became a new nation.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Romania would unite all Romanian-speaking people under a single state, leading to Greater Romania.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In Australia and New Zealand, the Battle of Gallipoli became known as those nations' "Baptism of Fire".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] It was the first major war in which the newly established countries fought, and it was one of the first times that Australian troops fought as Australians, not just subjects of the British Crown, and independent national identities for these nations took hold.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] Anzac Day, named after the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC), commemorates this defining moment.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] In the aftermath of World War I, Greece fought against Turkish nationalists led by Mustafa Kemal, a war that eventually resulted in a massive population exchange between the two countries under the Treaty of Lausanne.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p02] According to various sources, several hundred thousand Greeks died during this period, which was tied in with the Greek genocide.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] An estimated number of military and civilian casualties in World War I was about 15 to 22 million deaths and about 23 million wounded military personnel, ranking it among the deadliest conflicts in human history.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The total number of deaths includes between 9 and 11 million military personnel, with an estimated civilian death toll of about 6 to 13 million.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Of the 60 million European military personnel who were mobilised from 1914 to 1918, an estimated 8 million were killed, 7 million were permanently disabled, and 15 million were seriously injured.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Germany lost 15.1% of its active male population, Austria-Hungary lost 17.1%, and France lost 10.5%.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] France mobilised 7.8 million men, of which 1.4 million died and 3.2 million were injured.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Approximately 15,000 deployed men sustained gruesome facial injuries, causing social stigma and marginalisation; they were called the *gueules cassées* (broken faces).
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In Germany, civilian deaths were 474,000 higher than in peacetime, due in large part to food shortages and malnutrition that had weakened disease resistance.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] These excess deaths are estimated as 271,000 in 1918, plus another 71,000 in the first half of 1919 when the blockade was still in effect.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Starvation caused by famine killed approximately 100,000 people in Lebanon.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Diseases flourished in the chaotic wartime conditions.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In 1914 alone, louse-borne epidemic typhus killed 200,000 in Serbia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Starting in early 1918, a major influenza epidemic known as Spanish flu spread across the world, accelerated by the movement of large numbers of soldiers, often crammed together in camps and transport ships with poor sanitation.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Spanish flu killed at least 17 to 25 million people, including an estimated 2.64 million Europeans and as many as 675,000 Americans.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Between 1915 and 1926, an epidemic of encephalitis lethargica affected nearly 5 million people worldwide.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Eight million equines, mostly horses, donkeys and mules died, three-quarters of them from the extreme conditions they worked in.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The German army was the first to successfully deploy chemical weapons during the Second Battle of Ypres (April–May 1915), after German scientists under the direction of Fritz Haber at the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute developed a method to weaponise chlorine.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The use of chemical weapons had been sanctioned by the German High Command to force Allied soldiers out of their entrenched positions, complementing rather than supplanting more lethal conventional weapons.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Chemical weapons were deployed by all major belligerents throughout the war, inflicting approximately 1.3 million casualties, of which about 90,000 were fatal.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The use of chemical weapons in warfare was a direct violation of the 1899 Hague Declaration Concerning Asphyxiating Gases and the 1907 Hague Convention on Land Warfare, which prohibited their use.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The ethnic cleansing of the Ottoman Empire's Armenian population, including mass deportations and executions, during the final years of the Ottoman Empire is considered genocide.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Ottomans carried out organised and systematic massacres of the Armenian population at the beginning of the war and manipulated acts of Armenian resistance by portraying them as rebellions to justify further extermination.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In early 1915, several Armenians volunteered to join the Russian forces and the Ottoman government used this as a pretext to issue the Tehcir Law (Law on Deportation), which authorised the deportation of Armenians from the Empire's eastern provinces to Syria between 1915 and 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Armenians were intentionally marched to death and a number were attacked by Ottoman brigands.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] While the exact number of deaths is unknown, the International Association of Genocide Scholars estimates around 1.5 million.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The government of Turkey continues to deny the genocide to the present day, arguing that those who died were victims of inter-ethnic fighting, famine, or disease during World War I; these claims are rejected by most historians.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Other ethnic groups were similarly attacked by the Ottoman Empire during this period, including Assyrians and Greeks, and some scholars consider those events to be part of the same policy of extermination.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] At least 250,000 Assyrian Christians, about half of the population, and 350,000–750,000 Anatolian and Pontic Greeks were killed between 1915 and 1922.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] About 8 million soldiers surrendered and were held in POW camps during the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] All nations pledged to follow the Hague Conventions on fair treatment of prisoners of war, and the survival rate for POWs was generally much higher than that of combatants at the front.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Around 25–31% of Russian losses (as a proportion of those captured, wounded, or killed) were to prisoner status; for Austria-Hungary 32%; for Italy 26%; for France 12%; for Germany 9%; for Britain 7%.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Prisoners from the Allied armies totalled about 1.4 million (not including Russia, which lost 2.5–3.5 million soldiers as prisoners).
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] From the Central Powers, about 3.3 million soldiers became prisoners; most of them surrendered to Russians.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Allied personnel was around 42,928,000, while Central personnel was near 25,248,000.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] British soldiers of the war were initially volunteers but were increasingly conscripted.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Surviving veterans returning home often found they could discuss their experiences only among themselves, so formed "veterans' associations" or "Legions".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Conscription was common in most European countries, but was controversial in English-speaking countries.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] It was especially unpopular among minority ethnicities, especially the Irish Catholics in Ireland, Australia, and the French Catholics in Canada.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The administration decided to rely primarily on conscription, rather than voluntary enlistment, to raise military manpower after only 73,000 volunteers enlisted out of the initial 1 million target in the first six weeks of war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Military and civilian observers from every major power closely followed the course of the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Many were able to report on events from a perspective somewhat akin to modern "embedded" positions within the opposing land and naval forces.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Macro- and micro-economic consequences devolved from the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Families were altered by the departure of many men.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] With the death or absence of the primary wage earner, women were forced into the workforce in unprecedented numbers.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] At the same time, the industry needed to replace the lost labourers sent to war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The movement of women into industry and traditionally male labour ultimately aided the struggle for voting rights for women.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In all nations, the government's share of GDP increased, surpassing 50% in both Germany and France and nearly reaching that level in Britain.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] To pay for purchases in the US, Britain cashed in its extensive investments in American railroads and then began borrowing heavily from Wall Street.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] President Wilson was on the verge of cutting off the loans in late 1916 but allowed a great increase in US government lending to the Allies.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] After 1919, the US demanded repayment of these loans.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The repayments were, in part, funded by German reparations that, in turn, were supported by American loans to Germany.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] This circular system collapsed in 1931 and some loans were never repaid.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Britain still owed the United States $4.4 billion of World War I debt in 1934; the last installment was finally paid in 2015.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Britain turned to her colonies for help in obtaining essential war materials whose supply from traditional sources had become difficult.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Geologists such as Albert Kitson were called on to find new resources of precious minerals in the African colonies.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Kitson discovered important new deposits of manganese, used in munitions production, in the Gold Coast.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] However, neither of them interpreted it as an admission of war guilt.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In 1921, the total reparation sum was placed at 132 billion gold marks.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] However, "Allied experts knew that Germany could not pay" this sum.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] This figure could be paid in cash or in-kind (coal, timber, chemical dyes, etc.).
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Some of the territory lost—via the Treaty of Versailles—was credited towards the reparation figure as were other acts such as helping to restore the Library of Louvain.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] By 1929, the Great Depression caused political chaos throughout the world.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In 1932 the payment of reparations was suspended by the international community, by which point Germany had paid only the equivalent of 20.598 billion gold marks.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] With the rise of Adolf Hitler, all bonds and loans that had been issued and taken out during the 1920s and early 1930s were cancelled.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] David Andelman notes "Refusing to pay doesn't make an agreement null and void.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The bonds, the agreement, still exist." Thus, following the Second World War, at the London Conference in 1953, Germany agreed to resume payment on the money borrowed.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] On 3 October 2010, Germany made the final payment on these bonds.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Australian prime minister, Billy Hughes, wrote to the British prime minister, David Lloyd George, "You have assured us that you cannot get better terms.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In the Balkans, Yugoslav nationalists such as the leader, Ante Trumbić, strongly supported the war, desiring the freedom of Yugoslavs from Austria-Hungary and other foreign powers and the creation of an independent Yugoslavia.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Yugoslav Committee, led by Trumbić, was formed in Paris on 30 April 1915, but shortly moved its office to London.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In April 1918, the Rome Congress of Oppressed Nationalities met, including Czechoslovak, Italian, Polish, Transylvanian, and Yugoslav representatives who urged the Allies to support national self-determination for the peoples residing within Austria-Hungary.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In the Middle East, Arab nationalism soared in Ottoman territories in response to the rise of Turkish nationalism during the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Arab nationalist leaders advocated the creation of a pan-Arab state.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In 1916, the Arab Revolt began in Ottoman-controlled territories of the Middle East to achieve independence.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In East Africa, Iyasu V of Ethiopia was supporting the Dervish state who were at war with the British in the Somaliland campaign.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Several socialist parties initially supported the war when it began in August 1914.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] But European socialists split on national lines, with the concept of class conflict held by radical socialists such as Marxists and syndicalists being overborne by their patriotic support for the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Once the war began, Austrian, British, French, German, and Russian socialists followed the rising nationalist current by supporting their countries' intervention in the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Italian nationalism was stirred by the outbreak of the war and was initially strongly supported by a variety of political factions.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] One of the most prominent and popular Italian nationalist supporters of the war was Gabriele D'Annunzio, who promoted Italian irredentism and helped sway the Italian public to support intervention in the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Italian Liberal Party, under the leadership of Paolo Boselli, promoted intervention in the war on the side of the Allies and used the Dante Alighieri Society to promote Italian nationalism.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Italian socialists were divided on whether to support the war or oppose it; some were militant supporters of the war, including Benito Mussolini and Leonida Bissolati.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] However, the Italian Socialist Party decided to oppose the war after anti-militarist protestors were killed, resulting in a general strike called Red Week.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Italian Socialist Party purged itself of pro-war nationalist members, including Mussolini.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Mussolini formed the pro-interventionist *Il Popolo d'Italia* and the *Fasci Rivoluzionario d'Azione Internazionalista* ("Revolutionary Fasci for International Action") in October 1914 that later developed into the *Fasci Italiani di Combattimento* in 1919, the origin of fascism.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Mussolini's nationalism enabled him to raise funds from Ansaldo (an armaments firm) and other companies to create *Il Popolo d'Italia* to convince socialists and revolutionaries to support the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] On both sides, there was large-scale fundraising for soldiers' welfare, their dependents and those injured.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Around the British Empire, there were many patriotic funds, including the Royal Patriotic Fund Corporation, Canadian Patriotic Fund, and Queensland Patriotic Fund.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] By 1919, there were 983 funds in New Zealand.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] At the start of the next world war, the New Zealand funds were reformed, having been criticised as overlapping, wasteful, and abused, but 11 were still functioning in 2002.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Many countries jailed those who spoke out against the conflict.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] These included Eugene Debs in the US and Bertrand Russell in Britain.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In the US, the Espionage Act of 1917 and Sedition Act of 1918 made it a federal crime to oppose military recruitment or make any statements deemed "disloyal".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Publications at all critical of the government were removed from circulation by postal censors, and many served long prison sentences for statements of fact deemed unpatriotic.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Several nationalists opposed intervention, particularly within states that the nationalists were hostile to.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Although the vast majority of Irish people consented to participate in the war in 1914 and 1915, a minority of advanced Irish nationalists had staunchly opposed taking part.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The war began amid the Home Rule crisis in Ireland that had resurfaced in 1912, and by July 1914 there was a serious possibility of an outbreak of civil war in Ireland.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Irish nationalists and Marxists attempted to pursue Irish independence, culminating in the Easter Rising of 1916, with Germany sending 20,000 rifles to Ireland to stir unrest in Britain.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The British government placed Ireland under martial law in response to the Easter Rising, though once the immediate threat of revolution had dissipated, the authorities did try to make concessions to nationalist feeling.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] However, opposition to involvement in the war increased in Ireland, resulting in the Conscription Crisis of 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Other opposition came from conscientious objectors—some socialist, some religious—who had refused to fight.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In Britain, 16,000 people asked for conscientious objector status.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Some of them, most notably prominent peace activist Stephen Hobhouse, refused both military and alternative service.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Many suffered years of prison, including solitary confinement.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Even after the war, in Britain, many job advertisements were marked "No conscientious objectors need to apply".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] On 1–4 May 1917, about 100,000 workers and soldiers of Petrograd, and after them, the workers and soldiers of other Russian cities, led by the Bolsheviks, demonstrated under banners reading "Down with the war!" and "all power to the Soviets!".
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The mass demonstrations resulted in a crisis for the Russian Provisional Government.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In Milan, in May 1917, Bolshevik revolutionaries organised and engaged in rioting calling for an end to the war, and managed to close down factories and stop public transportation.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Italian army was forced to enter Milan with tanks and machine guns to face Bolsheviks and anarchists, who fought violently until 23 May when the army gained control of the city.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Almost 50 people (including three Italian soldiers) were killed and over 800 people were arrested.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] World War I began as a clash of 20th-century technology and 19th-century tactics, with the inevitably large ensuing casualties.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] By the end of 1917, however, the major armies had modernised and were making use of telephone, wireless communication, armoured cars, tanks (especially with the advent of the prototype tank, Little Willie), and aircraft.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Several types of poison gas were used by both sides.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Although it never proved a decisive weapon, it became one of the most feared of the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In 1914, cannons were positioned in the front line and fired directly at their targets.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] By 1917, indirect fire with guns (as well as mortars and even machine guns) was commonplace, using new techniques for spotting and ranging, notably, aircraft and the field telephone.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Fixed-wing aircraft were initially used for reconnaissance and ground attack.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] To shoot down enemy planes, anti-aircraft guns and fighter aircraft were developed.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Strategic bombers were created, principally by the Germans and British, though the former used Zeppelins as well.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Towards the end of the conflict, aircraft carriers were used for the first time, with HMS *Furious* launching Sopwith Camels in a raid to destroy the Zeppelin hangars at Tønder in 1918.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The non-military diplomatic and propaganda interactions among the nations were designed to build support for the cause or to undermine support for the enemy.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In addition, multiple peace proposals were coming from neutrals, or one side or the other; none of them progressed very far.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Memorials were built in thousands of villages and towns.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Close to battlefields, those buried in improvised burial grounds were gradually moved to formal graveyards under the care of organisations such as the Commonwealth War Graves Commission, the American Battle Monuments Commission, the German War Graves Commission, and Le Souvenir français.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Many of these graveyards also have monuments to the missing or unidentified dead, such as the Menin Gate Memorial to the Missing and the Thiepval Memorial to the Missing of the Somme.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In 1915, John McCrae, a Canadian army doctor, wrote the poem *In Flanders Fields* as a salute to those who perished in the war.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] It is still recited today, especially on Remembrance Day and Memorial Day.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] National World War I Museum and Memorial in Kansas City, Missouri, is a memorial dedicated to all Americans who served in World War I.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The Liberty Memorial was dedicated on 1 November 1921.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The British government budgeted substantial resources to the commemoration of the war during the period 2014 to 2018.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The lead body is the Imperial War Museum.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] As part of commemorations for the centenary of the 1918 Armistice, French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Angela Merkel visited the site of the signing of the Armistice of Compiègne and unveiled a plaque to reconciliation.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] The first efforts to comprehend the meaning and consequences of modern warfare began during the initial phases of the war and are still underway more than a century later.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Teaching World War I has presented special challenges.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] When compared with World War II, the First World War is often thought to be "a wrong war fought for the wrong reasons"; it lacks the metanarrative of good versus evil that characterises retellings of the Second World War.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Lacking recognisable heroes and villains, it is often taught thematically, invoking simplified tropes that obscure the complexity of the conflict.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Historian Heather Jones argues that the historiography has been reinvigorated by a cultural turn in the 21st century.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] Scholars have raised entirely new questions regarding military occupation, radicalisation of politics, race, medical science, gender and mental health.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] As late as 2007, unexploded ordnance at battlefield sites like Verdun and Somme continued to pose a danger.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In France and Belgium, locals who discover caches of unexploded munitions are assisted by weapons disposal units.
[src:world-war-i/world-war-i-p03] In some places, plant life has still not recovered from the effects of the war.
